<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Prices Up 0.1 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices increased
by a small 0.1 percent in May, the third consecutive increase,
the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The tiny gain in the U.S. Consumer Prices Index (CPI) brought
the seasonally adjusted annual rate of inflation for the year to
just 1.4 percent, less than half of the 3.3 percent price gain for
all of last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that it was more evidence that U.S. inflation
remained subdued despite a strong economic growth during the last
three months of 1996 and first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the slow increase of the CPI in the U.S.
last month mainly resulted from a 2.4 percent drop in energy
prices, the third decline in a row and the largest in six years.
But food prices were up by 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile food and energy sectors, the so-called
core prices rose a modest 0.2 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
This measure of so-called core inflation, which economists
believe to be a better measure of price trends, has been rising at
a 2.6 percent annual rate through May, the same as the core
increase for all of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
