<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States Beats China in World Youth Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALOR SETAR, Malaysia, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A last-minute goal
from Brian West gave the United States a 1-0 victory over China in
a Group C match at the World Youth Soccer Championship here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
West, at 18 the youngest player in the American camp, blasted a
small-angle shot from the left in the box after a previous shot
was deflected from Chinese goalie Li Leilei.
</P>
<P>
West, a student from University of Virginia who also scored the
winner in the 1-0 win over China in a friendly game in San Diego
in March, played only the last 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
American coach Jay Hoffman said West was still recovering from
a loose bowel.
</P>
<P>
China dominated most of match, especially the scoreless first
half which saw 12 attempts on the goal.
</P>
<P>
The team apparently lost much of steam in the second half.
After the West goal, they tried in vain in the last desperate
offence 30 seconds before the whistle.
</P>
<P>
Chinese coach Zhu Guanghu said, "The key to our loss today was
that we were loose in midfield. We also had problem in the
physical endurance in the second half.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone is feeling bad because we lost the game. But we would
play better in the coming two games," Zhu added.
</P>
<P>
Americans Chad McCarthy and Benjamin Oslen received yellow
cards from the referee Amand Ancion of Belgium. China's Zhang Ran,
Zhengyi and Zhang Xiaorui also got bookings.
</P>
<P>
In another Group C match, 1993 championship runner-up Ghana
beat Ireland 2-1.
</P>
<P>
Ghana's Bashiru Gambo scored the opening goal in 28th minute
but Trevor Molloy of Ireland levelled the score seven minutes
after the break.
</P>
<P>
Ghana's Mohamed-Kamil Mouktar netted the winning goal in the
67th minute with a deft placement.
</P>
<P>
Ghana, runners-up to Brazil in 1993 championships in Australia,
will meet China next on Thursday. Ireland takes on the United
States on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Asian champions South Korea and South Africa,
the African runners-up, played a goalless draw while Brazil
defeated France 3-0 in two group B matches at Kuching.
</P>
<P>
Alex DeSouza scored in the fifth minute to put Brazil 1-0 ahead
before the break before Adailton Martins netted 16 minutes into
the second half.
</P>
<P>
France's Michel Silvestre tapped the ball into his own goal in
the last minute when defending a Brazilian attack.
</P>
<P>
In the only group A match, Uruguay drubbed Belgium 3-0 in Shah
Alam.
</P>
<P>
The South American side scored its first goal in the 40th
minute when Inti Mezzetta Podesta fired a shot deflected off the
upright post but which he neatly slotted in on the second chance.
</P>
<P>
Walter Coelho's double, one in the 55th minute and other 77th,
made it 3-0 for Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay plays its next game against Malaysia on Thursday while
Morocco faces Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The 24 teams here are split into six groups and the top two
teams in each group plus four best third placers go into a
eliminatory second round. The final is to be played July 5 in the
Shah Alam stadium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
