<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on Cyprus's Purchase of Russian Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- It is the Cypriot government that
will decide if it would go ahead with a deal on the purchase of a
Russian surface-to-air missile system, a government spokesman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
At a daily press briefing, spokesman Manolis Christofides
said his government "has the inalienable right to decide if and
when progress is made toward a comprehensive settlement of the
Cyprus problem to warrant cancellation" of the missiles it bought
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's remarks came in response to statements by
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni Primakov and U.S. State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said after a meeting with Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides in Moscow Monday that the Russian-made
anti-aircraft missile system S-300 will be dispatched to Cyprus in
accordance with an agreement signed by the two countries earlier
this year, unless an agreement for the island's complete
demilitarization is reached.
</P>
<P>
The Russian minister also noted that Russia fully backs the
island's complete demilitarization as proposed by Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Primakov's statement, Burns reiterated U.S.
administration's opposition to the purchase of the Russian-made
anti-aircraft missile system by the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government's decision to purchase the Russian
missiles in January came under fire from the U.S. and some other
foreign governments, who feared this move will cause retaliatory
measures from Turkey and increase tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides has reassured worrying
diplomats here that no missile components will be delivered to
Cyprus in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot south and
Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when the Turkish troops invaded
and took control of the northern third of the island following a
short-lived Athens-backed coup.
</P>
<P>
Nine years after the division of the island, the Turkish
Cypriot side established a breakaway state "the Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus," which is recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
