<HEADLINE> Dutch, Scottish Cities to Host World Cup Cricket Matches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch town of Amstelveen and
the Scottish city of Edinburgh will both host a match in the 1999
cricket World Cup, organizers said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tournament director Terry Blake said at the official lauch at
Lord's on Tuesday that 42 matches would be staged at 21 venues.
</P>
<P>
The opening match between holders Sri Lanka and hosts England
on May 14 and the final on June 20 will both be held at Lord's.
</P>
<P>
Amstelveen will host the group A match between South Africa and
Kenya while first time qualifiers Scotland will play New Zealand
in Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
West Indies will take on Bangladesh at a venue in Ireland yet
to be decided.
</P>
<P>
The 12 teams have been divided into groups of six who will play
a round-robin competition.
</P>
<P>
The top three in each group will retain their points for the
second stage in which they will play the qualifiers from the other
group. The top four will proceed to the semi-finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
