<HEADLINE> Icelandair to Order RB211-535 Engines for New Boeing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Rolls-Royce is set to win orders
worth up to 200 million US dollars following Icelandair's decision
to buy four more Boeing 757 airliners, Rolls-Royce announced
today.
</P>
<P>
With the new order, Icelandair becomes the second airline, and
the first scheduled carrier, to select the latest 757-300 which
has a stretched fuselage to increase passenger payload, at the
same time reducing seat-mile operating costs.
</P>
<P>
An existing operator of four Rolls-Royce powered 757-200s,
Icelandair will use its new aircraft on the high-density routes to
North America, said a press release by the company.
</P>
<P>
A senior official from Rolls-Royce said, "Icelandair is one of
the oldest and most experienced airlines, so this new order is a
great endorsement of both the Boeing 757 and its Rolls-Royce
powerplant, RB211-535E4."
</P>
<P>
Deliveries of the airline's first two 757-200s are in
1998-1999, while the 757-300s with conversion rights to the -300
standard, have slots between 2000-2006, said Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
Icelandair has 40 years' relationship with Rolls-Royce, and its
first Rolls-Royce powered aircraft was the Viscount in 1957,
followed by the CL44 and Fokker F27 in the sixties, with the
Boeing 757 coming into service in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
