<HEADLINE> US Economist: Euro May Be 1st Real Competitor to Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A successful single European currency
could pose the first real competitor to the U.S. dollar as the
internationally dominant legal tender, a U.S economist was quoted
today by a German newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The creation of the planned common European currency, known as
the Euro, would be the most important event in the development of
the international currency system since the introduction of the
flexible exchange rates in the early 1970s, U.S. economist Fred
Bergsten was quoted by the German business daily Handelsblatt as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the dollar is still the dominant foreign
currency which settles about 40 to 60 percent of the world goods
trade, the European Union (EU) states as a whole have already
outnumbered the United States in economic output and foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent study conducted by Bergsten, the EU
boasts a total gross domestic product of 8,400 billion dollars
against 7,200 billion dollars of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Europe also chalked up an international trade of
1,900 billion dollars against 1,700 billion dollars registered in
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
In terms of ratio, the EU currently has a 31 percent share in
world output and a 20 percent share in world trade while the
comparable U.S. figures are 27 percent and 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bergsten noted that the increasing importance of Europe has
posed a big challenge to the United States, especially given the
fact that the U.S. is at present the world's biggest debtor nation
which is running up a trade deficit of over 200 billion dollars
annually.
</P>
<P>
"The consequences for the international currency system are
already perceptible even before the Euro is created," Bergsten
said.
</P>
<P>
"A successful Euro will come as the first real competitor to
the dollar since the U.S. currency replaced the British pound
sterling as the dominant foreign currency between the two world
wars," he said in conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
