<HEADLINE> New Generation Adour Engine to Be Certificated in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A new version of the Adour engine
has been launched by its Anglo-French makers, Rolls-Royce
Turbomeca, according to a press release here today.
</P>
<P>
The Adour 900 will embody the most modern technological
features that will ensure the engine continues to meet the most
challenging demands of military trainer and light combat
operations well into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The main features of the Adour 900 are a new design of
high-pressure compressor drum, a longer-life combustion chamber
and the very latest single crystal blading technology in both the
rotating and static aerofoils throughout the turbine, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
One notable feature will be the adoption of a FADEC
(full-authority digital electronic control system, including
integrated engine health monitoring. This will give the Adour 900
carefree handling, while reducing pilot workload and engine
maintenance back on the ground, it added.
</P>
<P>
Today's Adour powers all variants of the world-renowned Hawk
trainer/light combat aircraft, and the US Navy's T-45A Goshawk
advanced trainer.
</P>
<P>
Well over a million hours of service operation has been logged
by these single-engined aircraft, while the engine has accumulated
a total of 5 million flying hours in all aircraft types.
</P>
<P>
Rolls-Royce and Turbomeca have consistently taken a derivative
approach to product improvements by applying new technology to
ensure the Adour retains its competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
Both companies will participate fully in the Adour 900's
development program which will result in the engine's full
certification in 2000, according to Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
John Ferrie, who will be chairman of Rolls-Royce Turbomeca next
month, said, "The end result of the total enhancement package will
be an engine that will operate for twice as long between overhauls
based on typical existing Adour engine usage patterns."
</P>
<P>
"All reliability features of the existing Adour will be
retained, while the improvement modifications will be capable of
retrofit to other Adour variants in service with customers today,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
