<HEADLINE> Ties With Taiwan Brings Unrest to Sao Tome &AMP; </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The establishment of "diplomatic
ties" with China's Taiwan Province is bringing unrest to Sao Tome
&AMP; Principle, a high-ranking official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Braganca, Consultant to Raul Braganca Neto, Prime
Minister of Sao Tome &AMP; Principe, said the unrest is caused by the
presidential decree on the establishment of "diplomatic
relations" with Taiwan, as many government institutions oppose
the move.
</P>
<P>
Carlos made the remarks after extending a letter of Sao Tome &AMP;
Principe Prime Minister Raul Braganca Neto to his Angolan
counterpart Franca Van-Dunem.
</P>
<P>
He said that the letter is mainly about the island country's
unstable political situation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on establishing relations with Taiwan, which has
not got the approval by the government, is unlawful, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Carlos said a compromise that could be accepted by
most of the institutions must be found to get rid of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Sao Tome &AMP; Principe is an island country in the Gulf of
Guinea. A former Portuguese colony, it declared independence in
1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
