<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Clashes Continue in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- At least 19 Palestinian
protesters were injured by Israeli troops in the West Bank city
Hebron in the fourth consecutive day of clashes today.
</P>
<P>
Israeli state television quoted Palestinian hospital sources in
Hebron as saying that one 14-year-old boy was in critical
condition after sustaining serious wounds from rubber bullets
fired by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The rioting, which occurred near the Jewish neighborhood Beit
Hadassah, began when young Palestinian protesters burned an
Israeli flag and threw stones and fire bombs at Israeli soldiers
guarding the Jewish quarter. Israeli soldiers fired rubber bullets
and tear gas to disperse the protesters.
</P>
<P>
One Israeli soldier and 15 Palestinians were wounded Monday in
street battles in Hebron. In Sunday's clashes, there were two
Israeli soldiers and 15 Palestinian protesters wounded in the
volatile city.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army today repeated the accusation against Palestinian
police for ignoring agreements to subdue the riots. Army officials
also expressed the fear about escalation of violence if the
situation continued.
</P>
<P>
Jewish settlers meanwhile complained that the Israeli troops
were not tough enough to restore order in the city.
</P>
<P>
The clashes in Hebron followed last Thursday's violence near
the Gush Katif settlement in the Gaza Strip where Palestinians
gathered to protest Israel's confiscation of their land. Israeli
soldiers fired tear gas and used force to drive away protesters
who tore down the fences erected by the settlers on the disputed
land.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, clashes erupted again in Gush Katif when Palestinian
protesters broke into the settlement trying to destroy crops. One
Palestinian was wounded by a Jewish settler who fired his pistol
from his tractor at the Palestinian crowds.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported dozens of Palestinians, most of them
policemen, set up tents today at the Gush Katif junction to
protest Israel's confiscation of their land.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to calm the tense situation, members of the joint
Israeli-Palestinian Civilian Committee held a meeting with both
Palestinian and Israeli police officers to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
The latest wave of violence highlights the rising tension
between the two sides because of the continued deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process. Peace talks have been frozen
since Israel began building the controversial Har Homa settlement
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Despite intensive mediation efforts launched by the U.S. and
Egypt, there is no immediate sign of bringing the peace process
back on track. This has heightened the fear about widespread
renewed violence in the Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
