<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Government Urged to Punish Sexual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Women's Department of the Zimbabwe
Congress of Trade Unions today said the government should come up
with a law requiring that anybody found guilty of plying sexual
harassment at workplaces should be fired.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gender, labour and democratisation workshop in
Harare, Head of the Department Miriro Pswarai said the cases of women
being sexually harassed at workplaces were on the increase both in
the private and public sectors.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of a protective legislation, most suffering women
were losing their jobs when they tried to speak out, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said, ''we need legislation to protect women because the
environment we are working in now is threatening and intimidating.''
</P>
<P>
''The harasser should be promptly fired if proven guilty, and the
matter be reported to police,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
The men, she said, were easily promoted while women could only go
up the ladder should they give in to sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
By failing to come up with relevant legislation, the government
was protecting some perpetrators, she said. enditem

