<HEADLINE> OAPEC Oil Prices Drop in First Quarter of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The oil prices for the
Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) dropped
by 20 percent in the first quarter of this year, according to an
OAPEC monthly report published today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the prices of OAPEC's basket of seven crudes
stood at 18.6 dollars per barrel in March, a drop of 4.9 dollars
per barrel compared to last December.
</P>
<P>
The OAPEC, founded in 1968 in Lebanon, now has 10 member states
including Algeria, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Egypt,
Kuwait, Iraq, Qatar, Libya, Saudi Arabia and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The increase of world oil supply, such as the return of Iraq to
world oil market under a U.N. oil-for-food deal and overproduction
by some OPEC members, and the decrease of demand were the factors
causing the decline of oil prices, the report said.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's 12 members have increased production by about one
million barrels per day (bpd) since November last year, reaching
27.05 million bpd in April this year, according to Kuwaiti oil
sources.
</P>
<P>
An extra 400,000 bpd of output from OPEC might be forthcoming
in the second half of the year, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expect Algeria, Qatar, Nigeria, Venezuela and
Indonesia might all add production capacity this year.
</P>
<P>
OPEC is expected to leave unchanged official quotas under its
25.03 million bpd ceiling when it meets in Vienna on June
25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
