<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Risks Agreeing to Watered-Down Treaty as Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- European Union leaders watered
down an already modest proposal for a new EU treaty today, dashing
the high hopes to take ambitious steps in European integration.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said the negotiations were running behind schedule
and some delegations warned that the talks, on the second day of
the EU summit in Amsterdam, could run well into late evening.
</P>
<P>
In the latest draft treaty presented by the Dutch EU
presidency, Britain, Ireland and Denmark were given opt-outs in EU
policies aimed to prompt closer cooperation in crime fighting and
immigration policy.
</P>
<P>
The leaders, drafting a new EU treaty for the 21st century,
failed to take major steps towards building a common foreign and
defense policy, by agreeing to appoint the unknown
secretary-general of the Council of Ministers, instead of a
high-level figure desired by France, to steer EU foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft text, EU states would agree to cooperate more
closely in such areas as asylum, immigration, visa policy and
crime fighting, but the veto remains in the fields of asylum,
immigration and refugee policy because of national sensitivities.
</P>
<P>
The Schengen agreement, which lifts border checks within most
of the EU states, would be incorporated into the EU, while
allowing Britain and Ireland, linked to the former through a
passport union, to retain their border checks and the right to set
their own visa, immigration and asylum policy.
</P>
<P>
Denmark's opt-out is a reiteration of a previous one,
reflecting its constitutional problems with passing sovereignty to
EU institutions. However, as a member of the Schengen group, it is
expected to remain part of the border-free zone.
</P>
<P>
On defense, Britain, Denmark and the bloc's neutrals -- Sweden,
Ireland, Finland and Austria -- were resisting calls for
integration of the Western European Union (WEU) defense club into
the bloc, seen by others as a step towards true integration.
</P>
<P>
The language in the text had been toned down, saying only that
the WEU might one day be in the EU.
</P>
<P>
The leaders were set to agree that the WEU would remain
independent, sub-contracted to carry out humanitarian,
peacekeeping and crisis management mission for the EU.
</P>
<P>
One of the toughest fights would be over flexibility, the idea
of letting some integrate faster that other. A number of
countries, worried that they would be left behind by eager
integrationists, want individual member states to have a veto over
such plans, but Germany, France and others are adamantly opposed
to this.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac told his colleagues Monday that
flexibility "only made sense if decisions are taken by majority."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
