<HEADLINE> Iraq Asks U.N. to Open Fourth Border Point </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has officially asked the
U.N. to open a fourth border point for transporting goods across
the Iraqi-Syrian border, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The INA said Nizar Hamdoon, Iraqi ambassador to the U.N., made
this demand in a letter to the chairman of the U.N. Sanctions
Committee on Iraq on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He told the chairman that the fourth border point will be
opened at al-Waleed Abu Shamat on the Iraqi-Syrian border in line
with its "oil-for-food" with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Three border points for transporting humanitarian goods have
been opened. They are Um Qasr Port in the south, Treibil on the
Iraqi-Jordanian border and Faida on the Iraqi-Turkish border.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Iraq has signed several contracts with Syrian
companies to import food, medicine and other daily necessities, in
a first step for the two countries to resume their normal
relations interrupted for the past 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad severed its diplomatic ties with Damascus in 1980
after the eight-year Iraq-Iran War broke out because Damascus
sided with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Their relations further worsened when Syrian troops joined in
the Gulf War in 1991 to fight Iraq troops after their invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
