<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Funding Problems Threaten US Higher Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A new study found that growing
enrollment, rising tuition and declining funding have put U.S.
colleges on a dangerous financial course and threaten to bar
millions of students from higher education.
</P>
<P>
The Rand Corp., conducting the study, said in a report that if
current campus trends continue into the next century, millions of
Americans will be denied the opportunity to go to college, the
Washington Post said today.
</P>
<P>
The Rand report concluded that neither public nor private
support of colleges is keeping pace with campus costs or student
enrollment.
</P>
<P>
It projected that by 2015, the number of full-time college
students will be 13 million, about 3 million more than now.
</P>
<P>
It noted that while the enrollment is growing, college tuition
costs are continuing to outpace inflation. Average college tuition
per student, adjusted for inflation, has nearly doubled in the
past 20 years, it said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, allowing the situation to continue for another 20
years, the report warned, more than 6 million students will be
forced out of higher education in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The report criticized both the federal government and states
for not making stronger financial commitments to higher education
and many colleges for their financial mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
The report urged universities to define their misions more
precisely, streamline services, and do more to measure faculty
productivity.
</P>
<P>
It also recommended universities share more of each other's
resources and try to save money by relying more on new computer
technology and the Internet as tools for class instruction and
scholarly research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
