<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Navigation Center Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Yangtze River Navigation
Center was established today in Taicang, a city near the river's
mouth in east China's Jiangsu Province, to provide navigation
services for Chinese and overseas vessels.
</P>
<P>
Growing from the Navigation Station of the Yangtze River Harbor
Supervision Bureau, the center aims at conducting unified
management of navigating vessels along the longest river in China.
</P>
<P>
In the past, vessels sailing into and out of the Yangtze River
had to anchor at Liuhe Town in Taicang to wait for navigators to
board. Now, navigators are able to board the ships as they sail,
thus saving about four hours.
</P>
<P>
Along 1,300 km of the river, the Yangtze River Harbor
Supervision Bureau has established more than 20 navigation places
in the cities of Nanjing, Shanghai, Wuhan and Jiujiang. And there
is a large team of well-trained navigators.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the navigators have led about 70,000 vessels from 59
countries and regions through the river.  
</P>
</TEXT>
