<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar on Tuberculosis Control Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A six-day regional seminar began
here today at the SAARC Tuberculosis Center on how to control the
disease effectively.
</P>
<P>
The seminar will discuss ways to coordinate the tuberculosis
control activities of government, private and non-governmental
organizations and for the experts of SAARC countries to conduct
training activities, the official RSS news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the seminar are India, Nepal, the Maldives and
Pakistan, all members of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), which also groups Bhutan, Sri Lanka and
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Dirgha Singh Bam, director of the SAARC Tuberculosis Center
and the National Tuberculosis Center of Nepal, said that as the
region is home to 40 percent of the tuberculosis patients in the
world, the DOTS system that was introduced last year has been an
appropriate technology.
</P>
<P>
On the recommendation of the World Health Organization, the
Directly Observed Treatment Short Course (DOTS) method was brought
into South Asia, where 1 million people die of tuberculosis every
year.
</P>
<P>
The world today has about 10 million tuberculosis patients and
about 3 million people die of the disease every year.
</P>
<P>
In Nepal, 80,000 people suffer from tuberculosis, which is the
cause of death for 16,500 people annually.
</P>
<P>
The DOTS method has been found effective in controlling
tuberculosis as patients are given drugs under strict supervision
of doctors or health workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
