<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Reserves Drop in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's foreign exchange
reserves stood at 1.623 billion U.S. dollars at the end of May
this year, much less than the 2.039 billion dollars at the close
of the 1995-96 fiscal year, Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the parliament that the government has
undertaken several measures to increase the level of foreign
currency reserves in the country.
</P>
<P>
The measures include removal of problems of exporters to speed
up their export activities and steps to increase remittances from
expatriates, attract foreign investment and expedite the
implementation of foreign-aided projects to ensure availability of
foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
Kibria also told the parliament that the total amount of
default loans with banks was 141.59 billion taka (about 3.29
billion dollars) up to March 1996. "Party influence and sympathy
were considered in sanctioning most of such loans," he said.
</P>
<P>
After the present government took over last June, the finance
minister said, an amount of 20.03 billion taka (about 470 million
dollars) had been reduced from the total default bank loans during
the period from January to April 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
Kibria said the government has taken several measures including
the formation of a task force and reform of law to realize the
rest of the default loans.
</P>
<P>
Bankruptcy Act, 1997 has also been enacted, which will come
into effect soon for the realization of default loans, the finance
minister added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
