<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Change for HK Stock Exchange Beyond 1997: Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Stock Exchange
will have no change in its trading system and regulatory standards
after Hong Kong returns to China on July 1, Dr. Edgar Wai-kin
Cheng, chairman of the Council of the Exchange said here today.
</P>
<P>
Cheng made these remarks at a forum on prospects of the Hong
Kong stock market, which was hosted by the Better Hong Kong
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Cheng co-chaired the forum with Charles Yeh Kwong Lee, former
chairman of the Council of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, and
Nellie K.M.Fong, J.P., chairwoman of the executive committee of
the Better Hong Kong Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong, which commenced trading in
April, 1986, now has a market capitalization of nearly 4,000
billion Hong Kong dollars. It ranks seventh in the world and
second in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Cheng attributed the rapid growth of the Hong Kong stock market
to a well-regulated trading system, a high degree of liquidity and
the application of the same standards to all investors and listed
companies.
</P>
<P>
"All these will not change after July 1. We will maintain all
the existing standards and make sure that the market is
transparent, orderly and fair," he said.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the question of if there is competition between
the Hong Kong Stock Exchange and the Shanghai Securities Exchange,
Charles Lee said: "We are not competing with but complementing
each other, for we have different regulatory and supervisory
systems."
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that the Shanghai Securities Exchange has
advantages in handling domestic funds, while the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange is the right place to raise foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that Hong Kong could play a significant role
in raising capital for the modernization drive in inland areas,
and that the Hong Kong Stock Exchange has all along been serving
"as a link between international investors and Chinese state
enterprises."
</P>
<P>
To date, 28 enterprises from China's interior areas have been
listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, raising a total of five
billion US dollars on initial listing.
</P>
<P>
"Many (people) indeed see Hong Kong as having the potential and
capacity to become the 'Wall Street' of China in the future," Lee
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
