<HEADLINE> Afghan Northern City Falls to Taliban Militia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
Militia have taken the capital city of the northern Afghan
province of Kunduz, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The city of Kunduz, about 250 kilometers north of Kabul, fell
to the Taliban on Tuesday, the reports quoted the Taliban's
spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
If the reports are true, the Taliban's capture of Kunduz would
be the first major victory in northern Afghanistan since their
debacle in the northern city of Mazar-e-Sharif last month.
</P>
<P>
Briefly in May, the Taliban controlled roughly 90 percent of
Afghanistan, but a falling-out with their Uzbek allies led to
their defeat in Mazar-e-Sharif, a city some 300 kilometers north
of the Afghan capital.
</P>
<P>
Within days the Taliban were routed elsewhere in the north,
losing territory to the anti-Taliban alliance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
