<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Extravagance Fight Yields Results in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The national anti-extravagance
fight targeting government officials has yielded positive results
in its initial stage, according to statistics from the Central
Commission for Disciplinary Inspection of the Chinese Communist
Party (CPC).
</P>
<P>
The commission put a frugality program at top of the Party's
anti-corruption drive agenda for this year at a conference
in January.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President and General Secretary of the CPC Central
Committee Jiang Zemin called for all the Party members at the
meeting to "work hard and live a plain life."
</P>
<P>
The Party central committee and the State Council also issued a
set of Regulations on Party and Government Bodies Practicing
Thrift and Preventing Extravagance and Waste.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that local governments have so far saved
more than 1 billion yuan (about 120.48 million US dollars) by
putting a stop to or delaying the construction of some 80 office
buildings.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Jining in east China's Shandong Province, a
massive 12-million-yuan interior decoration project planned for an
office building was later changed to only a maintenance job, which
cost a maximum of 1 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The central government departments and local authorities have
also saved over 10 million yuan by canceling or reducing the
number and scale of meetings.
</P>
<P>
In provinces of Guangdong, Shandong, Hubei and Sichuan and
Tianjin Municipality, more than 4,000 residential telephone lines
and 6,000 mobile phones bought with public money and in violation
of State rules, were discovered and have been removed.
</P>
<P>
Cases of a number of luxury cars used by officials were
investigated and more than 40 expensive overseas tours funded by
public coffers have been stopped prior to departure.
</P>
<P>
Local Party and government departments have stepped up their
inspection efforts in finding waste and extravagant activities
among their own, said the commission.
</P>
<P>
East China's Zhejiang Province launched a series of surprise
checkups at 1,030 luxurious hotels and recreational centers in May
to find out who were disobeying the rules. And in Hubei Province,
122 big-spending party officials were disciplined for their
actions, and 146 units were given fines totaling more than 400,000
yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
