<HEADLINE> S. Leoneans Urged to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 18 (Xinhua)-- The head of the military junta in
Sierra Leone, Major Johnny Paul Koroma, Wednesday urged Sierra
Leoneans who fled the country after the June 2 Nigerian naval
bombardment to return home.
</P>
<P>
Koroma said those who have fled the country should come home
and assist the government in finding a solution to the current
political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the May 25 coup, who was speaking to religious
leaders, said, ''running away can never solve the problem''.
</P>
<P>
The State Radio, meanwhile, broadcast his appeals for all
Sierra Leoneans to return.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of doctors, lawyers, judges and administrators fled the
country by sea and land route to Guinea after renewed fears of
another Nigerian-led forces' attacks on the capital.
</P>
<P>
The radio called on both the Governor of the Central Bank, Steve
Swaray, and his deputy Enid Gibril to return saying their safety
is assured.
</P>
<P>
Immigration sources said up to 30,000 Sierra Leoneans are now
out of the country with the bulk in Guinea and Gambia.
</P>
<P>
Consular officials at the Guinea Embassy in Freetown said about
1,000 vehicles from Freetown had been issued with authorisation
to enter the Guinean territory.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) issued a
statement asking Sierra Leoneans to " forgive all atrocities
committed during the six-year-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
"We did not take to the bush because we want to be barbarians
but we want to state our humanhood to a society that looked on us
as subhumans," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the RUF has not denounced attempts to bring
deposed President Kabbah back. enditem


=06181416

=06181229
NNNN
22:22 22:22 g # PAB
</P>
