<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus More Than Triples in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus in
May jumped 222.2 percent from a year earlier to 738.27 billion yen
(6.5 billion U.S. dollars), the Finance Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The sharp surge of trade surplus reflected the yen's weakness
against the U.S. dollar, the ministry said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar was once traded at as high as 127 yen in early
May, which facilitateed Japan's exports of automobiles,
semiconductors and other goods.
</P>
<P>
Of Japan's global trade in May, exports increased 20.5 percent
to 4,104.88 billion yen (36.3 billion U.S. dollars), the 22nd
consecutive monthly expansion, while imports grew 6.0 percent to
3,366.61 billion yen (29.8 billion U.S. dollars), the 37th
straight monthly rise.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United
States totaled 322.87 billion yen (2.9 billion dollars), up 93.0
percent from a year earlier due mainly to expanding exports of
automobiles and office supplies.
</P>
<P>
Its exports to the U.S. advanced 22.9 percent to 1,104.11
billion yen (9.8 billion U.S. dollars) while imports expanded 6.8
percent to 781.24 billion yen (6.9 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Japan also posted increases in its goods trade surplus with the
European Union (EU) and Asia, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the EU soared 230.5 percent to 206.56 billion
yen (1.9 billion U.S. dollars), while that with Asian countries
rose 72.8 percent to 578.02 billion yen (5.1 billion U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
