<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Defense Secretary Ends Gulf Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen today ended his five-day Gulf tour after leaving the
Omani capital Muscat for home.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Oman, the last leg of his tour
which has taken him to Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Bahrain and the
United Arab Emirates (UAE), he held talks with Oman's Sultan
Qaboos and other top Omani leaders on Gulf security and the
latest developments in the Middle East region, the Omani news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also reiterated during his visits to other Gulf
countries that the U.S. will continue to keep a strong military
presence in the region to maintain interests of the U.S. and all
its Gulf allies.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. troops will continue to stay in the Gulf region
to strengthen defense ties with the regional states and
Washington will go ahead with its long-term commitment to Gulf
security, Cohen told Gulf leaders during his first tour to the
region as U.S. defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military presence in the Gulf currently includes
around 20,000 troops, 26 warships and hundreds of warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also said that Washington will maintain tough policies
against Iran and Iraq, the real threats to the Gulf states claimed
by the U.S. for a long time.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. policy towards Iran would not change unless Tehran
showed a marked shift from its support for international
terrorism and its keenness to buy and develop more weapons, the
U.S. defense official repeatedly stressed during his tour.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. also favored maintaining UN sanctions against Iraq
until Baghdad complied with all 1990-1991 Gulf crisis-related UN
resolutions and the collapse of Iraq's President Saddam Hussein,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the latest developments in the Middle East peace
process, the US defense secretary explained to Gulf leaders
that a recent vote by the U.S. House of Representatives
declaring Jerusalem as Israel's unified capital is not of the
opinion of U.S. President Bill Clinton's administration.
</P>
<P>
The non-biding resolution, opposed by Bill Clinton's
administration, was passed last week and set aside 100 million
dollars to move the US embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.
The vote has sparked criticism among the Arab world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
