<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia's Major Party Names New Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's biggest party, the
People's Revolutionary Party, today named general secretary
N. Enhbayar as its chairman to replace Nachagyn Bagabandy who was
elected the country's president last month.
</P>
<P>
At its third congress, the party also named L. Enebish as the
new general secretary.
</P>
<P>
Enhbayar, 39, said after his election that he will revamp the
party, which had governed Mongolia for more than 70 years before
being ousted from the government last year by a four-party
coalition led by the National Democrats and the Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Enhbayar, who can speak fluent English and Russian and is seen
as a key reformist in the party, said his party will begin
preparations for the next parliamentary election in 2000 and the
presidential poll the following year. He also hoped to cooperate
with other parties.
</P>
<P>
Bagabandy, who scored an overwhelming victory in the May 18
presidential election and is due to be inaugurated on Friday, is
forbidden by law to retain partisan membership.
</P>
<P>
Born in Ulan Bator and educated in the Moscow Golkii Literary
Institute, Enhbayar was the culture minister and a member of the
Great Hural (parliament) before last June's parliamentary poll.
</P>
<P>
He became the People's Revolutionary Party chief in July,
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
