<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Legislator Stresses Importance of Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The protection of the environment
and its resources should be guaranteed by law, a top Chinese
legislator said here today at a forum sponsored by the National
People's Congress, China's highest legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Environmental and resource protection is directly related to
the overall situation of China's economic growth and social
progress, and also to the well-being and development of future
generations, said Qiao Shi, chairman of the Standing Committee of
the NPC.
</P>
<P>
Since China's reform and opening-up, the protection work has
made tremendous headway as a result of more funding and increased
legal support, and the environment in some areas has been markedly
improved, said Qiao who is also a member of the Standing Committee
of the Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee.
</P>
<P>
However, the task of environmental protection on the whole
remains difficult, Qiao said, calling for the protection and
reasonable exploitation of oceans, grassland, minerals, living
things, land, water and forests.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Qiao urged local people's congresses and their
standing committees to strengthen law-enforcement in this regard.
</P>
<P>
During the five-day forum, participants said that the NPC and
lower legislative bodies should set as priority law-enforcement
inspections on arable land, trees and water.
</P>
<P>
Environmental and resource protection should be considered a
key point when appraise the work of local officials, Qiao
said. Those who are responsible for deteriorating environmental
conditions will not be promoted, and those involved in serious
cases will be removed from their posts.
</P>
<P>
Courts and procuratorates should be more active in handling
cases related to environmental and resource protection, said
participants at the forum.
</P>
<P>
In the coming years, China will purify some seriously polluted
lakes and rivers, and treat pollution in township enterprises and
urban sewage and garbage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Wholesale Trade Up in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Canadian wholesale trade value
reached 16.7 billion U.S. dollars in April, three percent higher
than in the previous month, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
The increase is in line with the strong sales recorded in the
first two months of 1997 and the upward movement that began in
early 1996, the federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
Higher sales were reported for most sectors, except for
computers and packaged software and food products.
</P>
<P>
Motor vehicles and parts and industrial machinery and
equipments were the biggest gainers, contributing over two-thirds
to the total increase, mainly due to renewed consumer confidence
and lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Canada's wholesale trade has accumulatively expanded 15.8
percent since it started picking up in January 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
