<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Choice by Ann Tze-Kai (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- For 85-year-old Ann Tze-Kai, a
prominent Hong Kong businessman, it's again the time for him to
contemplate the future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
But this time, his frame of mind is totally different from that
48 years ago.
</P>
<P>
When the People's Republic of China was founded in 1949, Ann,
just like many other residents in Hong Kong, asked himself where
Hong Kong, closely linked with the inland areas, would move.
</P>
<P>
Having gone through all the humility and hardships as a result
of the Japanese invasion and occupation of the Chinese mainland
and Hong Kong during the 1937-1945 period, Ann was so excited that
the Chinese nation had finally stood up. But he had just started
his textile industry then, and what if Hong Kong was turned into a
battlefield again?
</P>
<P>
"Every Chinese hopes that Hong Kong will return to China at an
early date, and that their motherland will become strong," Ann
said. "But how should Hong Kong return to the motherland in a way
that will benefit both the state and Hong Kong? I was really
unsure of that then."
</P>
<P>
To the surprise of Ann and all other Hong Kong residents, the
People's Liberation Army did not advance into Hong Kong. Moreover,
the first generation of leaders of new China explicitly put
forward the policy of making full use of Hong Kong, and
formulated a series of special policies on safeguarding Hong
Kong's stability and prosperity. To this end, the inland areas
have been providing large amounts of water, fresh vegetables, meat
and eggs for Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
"China then had the ability to resume the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong, "Ann said, "but the newly founded
people's republic needed a stable and peaceful international
environment to heal its wounds of war and carry out socialist
construction," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that maintaining a stable and prosperous Hon Kong
would help China break the blockade imposed by Western Countries
and expand its economy.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that handling the Hong Kong issue by peaceful
and rational means is conducive to Hong Kong's prosperity and
development, and is in the fundamental interest of the whole
nation as well.
</P>
<P>
With national invigoration as his greatest aspiration, Ann
devoted himself to expanding his own business. Along with the
growth of Hong Kong, he became one of the most prominent business
people in Hong Kong. Refusing to totally give up his dream of
becoming a linguist, Ann also rose to fame for his research into
Chinese characters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Choice by Ann Tse-Kai (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1970, Ann was appointed a member of the Legislative Council
of Hong Kong. Four years later, he became a member of the
Executive Council. In March 1993, 81-year-old Ann was elected a
vice-chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
All through the years, Ann has been eager to see that China
will become strong, and Hong Kong will return to the motherland
in a way that will benefit the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
Ann is all for Deng Xiaoping's "one country, two systems" idea.
"This is a concept that is both bold and ingenious."
</P>
<P>
He explains that no other country has ever allowed the
existence of two social systems within its border.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's present systems are suited to its development and
 Maintaining Hong Kong's capitalist system is beneficial to its
prosperity and stability, he said, noting that a prosperous and
stable Hong Kong is conducive to China's future development.
</P>
<P>
Ann took an active part in making preparations for the
establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR). In April 1985, he became a vice chairman of the Drafting
Committee of the Basic Law of the HKSAR. He also took part in the
whole process of the drafting work that spanned four years and
eight months.
</P>
<P>
Ann has also worked for the establishment of the HKSAR in other
capacities -- Advisor on Hong Kong Affairs, vice chairman of the
Preliminary Working Committee of the Preparatory Committee for the
HKSAR, and vice chairman of the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
Looking back at the 13-year transition period for Hong Kong,
Ann said, "It has actually been the whole process for realizing
step by step the idea of 'one country, two systems'. I feel very
happy that we have eventually found the best way and time to
resume the exercise of China's sovereignty over Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Despite his advanced age and although he has just recovered
from an illness, Ann pledged to attend the handover ceremony from
midnight of June 30 to early morning of July 1.
</P>
<P>
"I will definitely go to attend the ceremony because I am so
happy," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft HK Reunification Bill 1997 Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A draft Hong Kong Reunification
Bill 1997 was presented today to the Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) so that the views of PLC members will be taken into
account before the Bill's formal presentation on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill was handed by the Chief Executive's office of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), which will be
established on July 1 when China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the objectives of the bill, a spokesman for the
Chief Executive's office said that in accordance with the decision
made by the Preparatory Committee of the HKSAR in February 1997,
the laws that have been passed by the PLC before July 1 shall be
ratified upon the establishment of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt about the validity of the laws passed before
July 1," he said, "but the confirmation process on July 1 would
serve as an added assurance."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that it would be beneficial to the public
to be given an account of all the laws passed by the PLC prior to
July 1.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill contains provisions for the endorsement of the
appointment of the Chief Justice of the Court of Final Appeal,
Justices of the Court of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the
High Court, which under Article 90 of the Basic Law for the HKSAR
must be endorsed by the Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
It also deals with the adaptation of names and titles in the
laws, some with outdated references, in line with the resolution
of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress,
China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Another aim of the bill is to provide for various
transition-related matters, according to the spokesman, who adds
that it puts beyond doubt that the working of the government and
courts will continue after July 1.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there should be legislation establishing those
courts as well as quasi-judicial statutory tribunals and boards in
accordance with the Basic Law, and the legislation should also
provide that the laws previously applicable to such courts,
statutory tribunals and boards shall be maintained in respect of
them.
</P>
<P>
There should therefore be provision in the legislation for the
continuance of legal proceedings commenced before July 1 and for
other aspects of the administration of justice, the spokesman
added.
</P>
<P>
He said the bill also has provisions dealing with the
continuance of Hong Kong's current public servant system, and
preserves the rights and obligations of the existing government
and transfer them to the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill will be deliberated by the PLC at its meeting on
June 21, and views expressed will be included in the blue bill to
be gazette and presented on July 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Publishing Conference to Be Held in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Publishing experts in the
Asia-Pacific region will gather in Hong Kong from July 23 to 25 at
the first-ever Asian Publishing Conference, the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC) announced today.
</P>
<P>
The conference is one of the highlights of the Eighth Hong Kong
Book Fair, the largest book fair in Asia, which will take place
from July 23 to 28 at the expanded Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center (HKCEC).
</P>
<P>
TDC's Assistant Executive Director (Exhibition) C.S. Lee, said
that the conference, co-organized by the TDC and the Hong Kong
Publishing Federation, will provide a platform for members of the
publishing industry in the region to exchange ideas and to explore
co-operation opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the ideal venue to host the Asian Publishing
Conference, being a regional publishing hub and backed by a highly
developed printing industry which ranks the fourth in the world,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"Many major international publishers of newspapers, magazines
and books have their Asian headquarters here. The publishing
industry benefits from Hong Kong's excellent communications
network," he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the director of Hong Kong Publishing Federation,
Chan Man-hung, Chinese publishing is an important topic to be
covered in the conference.
</P>
<P>
He said: "It has already been recognized by international
publishers that Chinese publishing is the biggest market to be
developed in the next decade."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong, with its experience and expertise in dealing with
both the English and Chinese languages, plays an important role in
bridging the Chinese publishing with international publishers," he
added.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 exhibitors are expected to participate the first
book fair after Hong Kong's return to the motherland, organized by
TDC and supported by 11 local publishing associations.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 300,000 people visited the book fair. With the event
expanding to the HKCEC Extension this year, a higher attendance is
expected this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
