<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veterans Gather To Mark Anti-Japanese War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 Chinese generals and
veterans gathered here today to mark the 60th anniversary of the
July 7th Incident -- the beginning of Japan's War of Aggression
against China.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the get-together were family members of late
veterans who fought in the resistance war, as well as other people
from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
On July 7, 1937, the Japanese army fired on the Chinese army
near Lugouqiao Bridge, or "Marco Polo Bridge" west of Beiping,
which is now Beijing, in their attempt to annex the whole of
China. The event marked the start of the Chinese people's
eight-year national war of resistance against Japan.
</P>
<P>
Today, generals and soldiers alike told war stories, denounced
the criminal activities of Japanese invaders and lamented the
suffering endured by the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Many of the participants said they hope the people of China
will remember this period of history, and learn from it that a
weak and backward country is vulnerable to a stronger power. They
also agreed that the spirit of patriotism shown by the Chinese in
the anti-Japanese war should be passed on from generation to
generation.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, a photo exhibition titled "Atrocities of the
Japanese Invaders in China" opened, featuring more than 300
historical photos illustrating the murders, rapes and other
criminal acts committed by the Japanese army from 1937 to
1945.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
