<HEADLINE> Japan's Diet Ends Regular Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Diet (parliament) today
wrapped up its 150-day annual session after passing some important
bills, including one clearing the way for organ transplant.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that deliberations have been generally smooth
since the regular session convened on January 20, without any
major clashes between the ruling and opposition camps.
</P>
<P>
During the session, the 77.39 trillion yen (684.9 billion
dollars) national budget for the 1997 fiscal year was passed
without amendments on March 28, in time for the new fiscal year
starting on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a bill was also adopted to establish a new finance
industry watchdog body, independent of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under Japan's parliament law, the Diet normally begins the
150-day regular session in December to discuss important state
affairs. 
</P>
