<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR PC Makes Historical Contributions to HK's Smooth Transition (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Preparatory Committee of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) has made
historical contributions to the smooth transition of Hong Kong and
to the formation of the HKSAR since it was founded 16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee is an organ set up on the
authorization of the National People's Congress. Its main task is
to establish the first government of the HKSAR and its legislature
in accordance with stipulations provided by the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year and more, the committee adhered to the
principle of "Catering to the Hong Kong People and relying on
them", aroused the enthusiasm among Hong Kong people for
participating in the formation of the HKSAR and brought about a
good situation of greeting the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, the committee has held nine plenums, completing the
following seven tasks:
</P>
<P>
-- forming a Selection Committee which is composed of 400
members who are all permanent Hong Kong residents;
</P>
<P>
-- electing the first chief executive of the HKSAR;
</P>
<P>
-- forming through election a 60-member Provisional Legislative
Council;
</P>
<P>
-- putting forward proposals, after a systematic study, on
those existing Hong Kong laws to be not changed basically;
</P>
<P>
-- studying and raising suggestions on a series of major
economic issues such as the composition of the 1997-98 fiscal
budget, issues on monetary stability, handover of government
assets and construction of large infrastructure projects;
</P>
<P>
-- pushing ahead with the formation of the Committee for
Activities to Mark Hong Kong's Return to the Motherland by Various
Sectors in Hong Kong and preparing for various non-governmental
activities and
</P>
<P>
-- formulating specific methods on the formation of the first
Legislative Council of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
It is a major task for the Preparatory Committee to form a
400-member Selection Committee. It shoulders the tasks of
selecting the first chief executive of the HKSAR and electing the
provisional legislative council members. The Preparatory Committee
has made unremitting efforts in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In April last year, 16 meetings were held in Hong Kong by the
Preparatory Committee, soliciting opinions among Hong Kong
residents. Over 1,000 people from 366 sectors and organizations
took an active part in the meetings. As a result about a
10,000-character report on the opinions solicited from local
residents was made public
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
