<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3.6 Billion Dollars to Be Spent on Revitalizing State Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
allocated 30 billion yuan (over 3.6 billion US dollars) to write
off bad loans of merged or bankrupted enterprises.
</P>
<P>
During a recent inspection tour of south China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region and Hainan Province, Vice-premier Wu Bangguo
emphasized the importance of using the money wisely to get
enterprises back in the black and help laid-off employees find
work.
</P>
<P>
Wu, who is also a member of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), visited the area
from June 12 to 18.
</P>
<P>
He said that state-owned enterprises still play a leading role
in China's national economy, and that they have been noticeably
revitalized by the state's newly-instituted reforms. Nevertheless,
they still are not making satisfactory profits, he said.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged local officials to help these enterprises earn
more than they did last year.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier said that firms now face better market
conditions than ever before, especially in regard to consumer
goods, investment and exports. And bank loans have been
re-structured to better meet the needs of the state-owned
enterprises, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Wu called on state-owned enterprises to make the most of this
opportunity and increase their economic returns. Big
profit-earners should be granted more preferential policies and
given more space to develop, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of laid-off workers, Wu said that local
governments must see to it that the unemployed can make ends meet
and also encourage them to look for jobs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
