<HEADLINE> China's Human Rights Group Leaves Sweden for Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUND, Sweden, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of China's human
rights studies group left here today for Italy after a five-day
visit to Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The delegation headed by Zhu Muzhi, president of the Human
Rights Society of China, is on its second leg of a four-nation
European tour. The delegation had visited Norway, and will go on
to Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
During the visit to Sweden, Zhu and his delegation exchanged
views on human rights with Jan Romare, a Foreign Ministry official
in charge of human rights affairs, and Professor Goran Melander of
Lund University.
</P>
<P>
In talks with Professor Melander, Zhu said the visit is
designed to establish contact and dialogue with Swedish human
rights groups and scholars so as to promote mutual understanding,
clear up misunderstanding and strengthen cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed cooperation programs such as
co-sponsoring seminars, exchanging books and information and
exchanging visiting scholars.
</P>
<P>
Zhu and his delegation visited the oriental language department
of the university and exchanged views on human rights with the
professors and scholars of the department.
</P>
<P>
The delegation also met Swedish journalists and answered their
questions on human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
Zhu briefed them on China's judicial guarantee of human rights
and denied the rumor that Chinese has replaced Tibetan as the main
teaching language in the schools of the Tibet autonomous region.
</P>
</TEXT>
