<HEADLINE> Iraq to Resume Oil Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed
Rasheed announced here today that his country is to resume oil
exports under the renewed "oil-for-food" deal.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed made this announcement while commenting on earlier
reports that Iraq suspended its limited oil exports to the world
market.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi News Agency (INA) quoted Rasheed as saying that Iraq will
resume its limited oil exports as soon as a new distribution plan
on the oil revenues is reached by Iraq and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
He said that his ministry is continuing meetings to strike
deals with representatives of oil imports firms.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the U.N. Security Council extended the
"oil-for-food" deal for another six months. But before the
resumption of its oil exports, Iraq must submit a distribution
plan on the oil revenues to the U.N. Sanctions Committee on
Iraq for approval.
</P>
<P>
The first six-months period of the deal expired on June 7,
while the second came into force as of June 8.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Iraq is again allowed to sell 2 billion U.S.
dollars of oil over six months on a renewable basis to
raise cash for the purchase of humanitarian goods urgently
needed in the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been hit severely by the U.N.-imposed sanctions as
a result of its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
