<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Expect Euro to Start Punctually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- International financial experts
reacted to the two-day European Union summit in Amsterdam with a
widely-shared perception that the planned single European currency
"Euro" will come into life punctually on January 1, 1999, but will
be weaker than the German mark.
</P>
<P>
"The results of the Amsterdam summit confirmed our views that
there is no big risk of a delay in the European monetary union at
the moment," analysts with the ABN Amro Bank in Frankfurt were
quoted Wednesday by the German daily General Anzeiger as saying.
</P>
<P>
"All factors point to a European monetary union with a wide
participation but a weak Euro," Ron Leven, a JP Morgan currency
expert, told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
EU leaders in their meeting in Amsterdam have agreed to a
compromise budget stability plan that would keep the single
currency on track while accommodating French concerns about the
need for more efforts to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
But the compromise also made clear that Germany and France, the
two nations at the heart of the monetary union, had fundamental
differences in monetary and fiscal policy after the Euro is
introduced, experts said.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that although Euro was expected to be able to
compete with the U.S. dollar in the long run, the open rifts
between major European nations would benefit the dollar at least
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
"Although the huge trade deficits in the United States speak to
the disadvantage of the dollar, the political development in
Europe meanwhile will bolster the currency emotionally," Ulrich
Ramm, chief economist of the German Commerzbank said.
</P>
<P>
A survey carried by the General Anzeiger also found out that a
majority of the German population remain mistrustful of Euro which
is expected to replace their rock-hard mark eventually.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that over 60 percent of the 1,500 respondents
were worrying about higher inflation after the introduction of
Euro, which means losses in the value of their bank deposits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
