<HEADLINE> hkhk-Zhou Nan Visits HK Convention, Exhibition Center Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Nan, director of the Hong
Kong Branch of Xinhua News Agency, today expressed the hope that
the remaining unfinished decoration of the Hong Kong Convention
and Exhibition Center (CEC) Extension will be completed on
schedule to ensure the successful holding of the handover
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
This Morning Zhou visited the extension where the decoration is
well in progress.
</P>
<P>
Located in the Victoria Harbor, the new extension built on 6.5
hectors of land reclaimed from the sea has five exhibition halls,
two conference halls and 52 conference rooms. It covers a total of
155,000 square meters. Its construction started three years ago.
</P>
<P>
While visiting the Grand Hall on Level Five and the foyer --
the venue for the handover ceremony to be held jointly by the
Chinese and British governments at mid-night on June 30, Zhou Nan
expressed thanks to the workers on the site, encouraging them to
overcome all kinds of difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In the Grand Hall on Level Seven, where a ceremony to mark the
establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) and a swearing-in ceremony of the HKSAR government and a
ceremony to celebrate the establishment of the HKSAR government
will be held on July 1 in succession, workers are busy decorating
the meeting places and installing chairs.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Nan expressed satisfaction with the progress of the
construction, noting that the extension will be a witness to Hong
Kong's return to the motherland, a historic event for the Chinese
nation and a great event which draws the attention of the whole
world.
</P>
<P>
The extension in the shape of a bird soaring into the sky will
also serve as a symbol of the vitality and the economic take-off
of Hong Kong, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the belief that with the support of the
motherland and concerted efforts of Hong Kong compatriots, Hong
Kong will certainly be able to achieve smooth transition and
continue to maintain its prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
