<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian-Made Fireworks to Light Up HK Harbor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian fireworks company
responsible for the New Year's Eve extravaganza on the Sydney
harbor is about to light up the Victoria Harbor in Hong Kong on
July 1.
</P>
<P>
The husband-and-wife company of Syd Howard Fireworks
International Pty Ltd., based at Glenorie near Berowra Waters in
Sydney's northern outskirts, has won a contract to provide
fireworks for Hong Kong to usher in its handover to China on July
1.
</P>
<P>
"The British are doing the withdrawal on June 30 and we do the
welcome on July 1," Jill Howard, who owns the company with her
husband, Syd, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
However, she refused to disclose the value of the contract,
saying this is forbidden under the contract with Better Hong Kong
Foundation, a group of 15 leading Hong Kong businesses organizing
the handover show.
</P>
<P>
"But in terms of what we've done before, it's the biggest in
terms of budget and size," she said.
</P>
<P>
Her husband and an Australian crew of 15 pyrotechnicians are
leaving for Hong Kong tomorrow along with 20 tons of fireworks and
80 tons of equipment to blast them into the night sky.
</P>
<P>
Asked if she found it a little strange that Australians are
selling fireworks to the Chinese, she said: "While the Chinese
have great expertise in fireworks, they haven't much practical
experience of large-scale international events."
</P>
<P>
Syd Howard Fireworks was involved in the 1996 Atlanta Olympic
Games opening and closing ceremonies, the 1988 Australian
bicentennial of European settlement, Australia Day celebration in
Sydney each January 26 and New Year's Eve celebration on the
harbor.
</P>
<P>
The last two shows employ tall buildings as launching pads for
fireworks, something that would have been ideal in Hong Kong with
its forest of concrete.
</P>
<P>
Jill, however, will be watching the handover of Hong Kong to
China from her Sydney suburban lounge room.
</P>
<P>
"It's an exciting thing but I'll be watching it on TV like
everyone else," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
