<HEADLINE> Expert Committee On Traffic Problems To Be Set Up In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The municipal government of
Beijing plans to set up an institution composed of experts and
officials to deal with planning and administrative matters
concerning the urban traffic problem.
</P>
<P>
Executive Vice-Mayor Zhang Baifa announced the plan at today's
municipal panel discussion on science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has experienced worsening traffic as the number of
vehicles rises remarkably. By the end of 1996, the city had 1.12
million motorized vehicles and 9.45 million non-motorized vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The number of jammed spots in the city increased to 99 in 1996,
from 27 in 1993. Over 50 cases of jamming occur in the main
thoroughfares on an average day. 
