<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Meets With EU Envoy on Syrian Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu asked today European Union (EU) peace
envoy Miguel Moratinos to convey a message to Syria for resuming
the Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the requirement during his meeting here with
Moratinos who is trying to break the deadlock in the
Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations that have stalled for over one
year.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Netanyahu's message to Syria is that
Israel hopes to resume the peace talks with Damascus without any
preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos is to travel to Damascus later today to hold
meetings with Syrian leaders on exploring ways to resume the
peace talks with Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
During his last mission to mediate between Israel and Syria
early May, the EU envoy conveyed a "message of peace" from
Damascus to Tel Aviv. He refuted the Israeli press reports that
Syria was not interested in making peace with Israel and was
preparing for war.
</P>
<P>
On May 4, Moratinos discussed with Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy a proposal to reactivate the peace talks on the basis
of the Madrid Conference, which imposes no preconditions on
either side.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding obstacle blocking the resumption of the talks
is Israel's refusal to make a promise on a full withdrawal from
the Golan Heights Israel has occupied. Under the previous Israeli
Labor government, Israel and Syria appeared on the verge of a
Golan-for-peace deal, but it was never finalized.
</P>
<P>
And the peace talks have been totally frozen since the
Netanyahu-led hardline Likud government came to power last
June. Despite his repeated calls for the resumption of the peace
negotiations, Netanyahu insists that the talks should be held
without any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
The continued deadlock on the peace track has led to rising
tension between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Israeli Army Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin Shahak
warned that Syria might resort to war with Israel if the peace
stalemate continued.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu said early this week that he currently saw no
immediate sign of war with Syria, though, he added, the Israeli
troops have been keeping vigilance against any possibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
