<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improved Environment in Tibet Attracting Rare Birds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A number of black necked cranes
returned this year to their home in Shigatse beside the Yarlung
Zangbo River in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands along the Yarlung Zangbo used to be an important
winter habitat for the cranes, but because of the expansion of
desertified land in some areas, the cranes began to return less
and less.
</P>
<P>
The Black-necked crane mainly exists in China and is under top
state protection. The number that appeared in Gyamtang this year
was much larger than in previous years, locals say. Experts
attribute this to afforestation efforts of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
A shelterbelt has been planted since 1994, greatly hold back
desertification. The Chinese Academy of Sciences' Lanzhou
Institute of Desert Research has successfully introduced seven
sandy plants into the region, helping green up both banks of the
Yarlung Zangbo.
</P>
<P>
"The green-up drive in the region of the past three years is a
key anti-desertification effort," said a researcher from the
Institute, "and it is also an important means of protecting
wildlife there."
</P>
<P>
According to a 1994 study, Tibet is home to nearly 4,000
black-necked cranes in wintertime, accounting for 70.9 percent of
this rare bird's total population in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
