<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian DNA Discovery Called Tool to Solve Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Australian scientists said they
have discovered a new, easier way to extract DNA, an individual
genetic blueprint which is often used by police to identify
criminals.
</P>
<P>
"Touching a pen, a glass or a steering wheel is enough to leave
a telltale genetic marker more durable than a fingerprint," the
Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The discovery provides a new tool for crime investigators
because until now it has been practicable to extract DNA only from
bodily matter such as hair, blood, semen or saliva left at a crime
scene.
</P>
<P>
Through a new technique, Roland van Oorschot and Maxwell Jones
of the Victoria Forensic Science Center have now found a way to
get traces of DNA from objects that come in contact with human
skin, including condoms and gloves.
</P>
<P>
While fingerprints can smudge or be rubbed off, the researchers
found that a person can be identified from as little as 1.1
billionth of a gram of genetic material, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Experiments with people holding telephones, pens, knives, mugs,
glasses or plastic tubes for as little as five seconds produced
enough DNA to identify the user while tests on objects used by
several people showed traces from all of them.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the latest edition of the science journal Nature,
the pair said DNA traces could be passed on to a second person
picking up the object, or from hand to hand.
</P>
<P>
Van Oorschot said the technique came into its own with crime
scene evidence when fingerprints were not present or difficult to
identify, such as with gloves and condoms.
</P>
<P>
Police officers in the state of Victoria has already used the
technique successfully in attempted murder, rape, armed robbery
and drug trafficking cases, although they were yet to come to
court, AAP said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0111 </DOCNO>
