<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Finds New Way to Increase Mango Yield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Green flies are being
cultivated in Malaysia as a way to increase mango yield because
the insect is found to be an excellent pollinating agent for
mangoes.
</P>
<P>
The green flies are cultivated by leaving rotting fish at the
trunk of mango trees, after which maggots would emerge and grow
into the adult insect, Malaysian national news agency Bernama
reported today quoting a government official.
</P>
<P>
"The flies flying around from flower to flower helps to
pollinate them," Hussin Yunus, Director of the Perlis State
Agriculture Department which is undertaking the exercise, was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The mango trees have markedly increased flowering since the
cultivation exercise began, and hopes of a bumper harvest are
high, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The department aimed to double the yield from the present 500
mangoes per tree each season to 1,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 130,000 mango trees over a total of 1,000
hectares in the state, of which 2,548 trees belong to five state
agriculture projects covering 182 hectares while the remainder are
privately cultivated in backyards and compounds.
</P>
<P>
The flies pose no danger to residents in the vicinity,
according to the official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China and Japan Joint TV Movies Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai, June 18 (xinhua) -- China may have the world's
largest TV audience, but the TV movie is still a stranger to most
of those hundreds of millions of viewers.
</P>
<P>
But not for long. Producers from the cities of Beijing and
Shanghai, from Guangdong Province, and from Hong Kong and Japan
are cooperating in producing China's first TV-movies.
</P>
<P>
Some call the TV-movie the new baby of the television
generation. It lies somewhere in between the TV series and
full-length cinemas.
</P>
<P>
But, some consider it better than both in a number of
ways. It's cheaper, at an average of 800,000 yuan each; it's
easier to shoot than a movie; and it can reach a larger audience
with that ubiquitous medium.
</P>
<P>
The difference between it and a TV series is that, although it
costs more to make, it is of higher quality in both audio and
video signal. TV-movies have a uniform length of one and half
hours. They are shot with either film or digital video tape, and
are shown exclusively on TV.
</P>
<P>
With a lineup already prepared, six movie and TV companies from
China and Japan have three action and romance pictures ready to
shoot. They will be shown in more than 80 cities in China, and
will be followed by 52 other productions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa Joins in International Initiative for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa, Germany,
Singapore and Brazil will launch a joint initiative later this
month for world environmental protection and sustainable
development, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued in Johannesburg by South African
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso, Singapore's Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong and
German Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl, the initiative will be
launched at a United Nations general assembly special session,
scheduled to begin on June 23 in New York.
</P>
<P>
The initiative's main objective is to achieve concrete
progress in key issues concerning international cooperation in
environment and development, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The four statesmen will focus on measures aimed at
climate and forests protection, urban development and issues of
anchoring global environmental protection institutionally to a
greater degree within the UN, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Five years after the UN Conference on Environment and
Development in Rio De Janeiro, Brazil, the UN will at the
forthcoming special session review the progress made so far to
determine future moves in international cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
