<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Syria to Coordinate Stance on Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Vice-President Abdul-Halim
Khaddam arrived here today to coordinate with the Iranian
government their stances toward Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam has brought with him a message from Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad to his Iranian counterpart Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani, the Iranian news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam and his entourage were met by Iranian First
Vice-President Hassan Habibi at the Mehrabad Airport.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian vice-president disclosed that Turkey's alliance with
Israel, the incursion of the Turkish forces into northern Iraq
and what he called the recent Israeli instigation in the region
will top the agenda of his talks with Iranian officials, the
IRNA report said.
</P>
<P>
On the Turkish military presence in Iraq, Khaddam said that
the Turkish troops under the pretext of creating a security zone
in Iraq is an outcome of the Ankara-Tel Aviv cooperation.
He termed the Turkish troops' incursion into northern Iraq as
an open aggression and violation of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
Habibi expressed Iran's interest in exchanging views with
Syria officials on regional issues, according the IRNA.
</P>
<P>
In regard to the recent U.S. Congress resolution to recognize
Jerusalem as the undivided capital of Israel, Habibi said it is
wrong and improper.
</P>
<P>
Stressing Iran's opposition to the move, Habibi noted that
Jerusalem belongs to Muslims of the world and the Jewish state has
no right to make any claim.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara and several
other high-ranking officials, Khaddam is on a one-day visit to
Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
