<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Tax Revenues Up 16.6 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial and commercial
tax revenues for May were up 16.6 percent on a yearly basis,
according to the State Administration of Taxation (SAT).
</P>
<P>
Monthly revenues from value-added tax and consumer tax, two
major taxes under China's new tax regime of 1994, were up only 5.2
percent last month, down 7.5 percentage points from April.
</P>
<P>
The SAT attributes the substantial slowdown to a relatively
large base figure for the same month last year. The two taxes were
normal, it said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a skyrocketing security trading volume and increases
in duties, stamp duties on securities trading amounted to 3.67
billion yuan last month, nearly ten times what they were a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
The SAT also said that tax rebates to exporters amounted to
4.13 billion yuan in May.
</P>
<P>
Between January and May, China's industrial and commercial tax
revenues were up 17.5 percent over the same period of last year
and were 40.6 percent of this year's target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
