<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seen on Right Path to Fiscal Revitalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The recent new tax system has put
China back on track towards fiscal revitalization, according to
financial officials and experts.
</P>
<P>
Since the adoption of a revenue-sharing tax system in 1994,
China's upward economic trends have been auspicious for the
nation's fiscal recovery, they noted in recent interviews with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that China's fiscal revenue outgrew spending
for the first time in more than a dozen years in 1995, by 18.6
percent against 17.6 percent. The margin expanded to two
percentage points last year. In the first quarter of this year,
China's fiscal revenue soared 29.3 percent on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
The national fiscal revenue has also recovered from a downward
trend as a proportion to the Gross Domestic Product (GDP),
accounting for 10.9 percent of the GDP last year. The proportion
of the central fiscal revenue in the national total has also
stopped falling and begun on a upward movement.
</P>
<P>
All these are clear indications that China's fiscal conditions
are turning for the better and are evidence of a successful start
of fiscal revitalization, a Ministry of Finance official said.
</P>
<P>
Echoing such a view were Pieter Bottelier, chief of the World
Bank's Resident Mission in China, and Liu Shangxi, a research
fellow with the ministry's Research Institute of Fiscal Science.
</P>
<P>
Accelerated growth in the national fiscal revenue in recent
years has helped check the expansion of the fiscal deficit, which
has shrunk to a manageable level, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Although China's overall fiscal strength has been expanding
continuously since the beginning of the reform and opening-up drive
in the late 1970s, its growth has lagged behind that of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the fiscal revenue has been shrinking as a share in
the GDP, down from the 25.7 percent in 1980 to 10.8 percent in
1995. The same thing also happened with the central fiscal
revenue, whose proportion in the national revenue went down from
the 38.4 percent in 1985 to 22 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
All these problems, together with fiscal expenditure growing
faster than revenue, have caused great strains in the national
finances, Liu Shangxi pointed out.
</P>
<P>
They have adversely affected the playing of fiscal functions,
harmed the effectiveness of economic macro-control policies and
forced the Central Government to rely more on issuing treasury
bonds, he said.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problems, China has officially announced a fiscal
revitalization plan in the outline of its Ninth Five-Year Plan for
National Economic and Social Development (1996-2000) and the
Long-Range Objectives to the Year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The plan was centered around lifting the "two proportions",
namely raising the national fiscal revenue to about 20 percent of
the GDP and the central fiscal revenue to more than 60 percent of
the national figure.
</P>
<P>
For the years to 2000, the targets include making the fiscal
revenue outgrow spendings and basically eliminating fiscal deficit.
</P>
<P>
"Though the worst had passed after the introduction of
the new tax system in 1994, China has just seen the start for fiscal
revitalization as there is still a long way to go to eventually
pull the national finances out of difficulties," said Li Yang, a
research fellow with the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Bottelier of the World Bank also said that fiscal strains are
an important factor affecting the sustained and long-term
development of the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal difficulties are an issue that China must deal with in
earnest, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Rival Parties Trade Accusations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The two rival Cambodian ruling
parties today traded accusations over violence Tuesday in the
capital which left two killed and one seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, first prime minister and head of the
Funcinpec party, was the target of the assault on Tuesday night,
Srey Kosal, spokesman for Ranariddh told the press at the prime
minister's official residence.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that a group of armed terrorists launched
attack on his and Ranariddh's residences under the command of
National Police Chief Hok Longdi, member of Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party (CPP)
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the two sides exchanged fires with
machine-guns, mortars and rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
However, Hok Longdi told reporters today at his home that the
violence was steered by the Funcinpec party and aimed to
assassinate Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
Hok Longdi said that his troops did not suffer casualties
because precautious measures were taken in advance.
</P>
<P>
A curfew has been imposed in some areas in the capital and
thousands of soldiers, police and militia units loyal to Funcinpec
and the CPP were posted around the city.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, which is scheduled to hold commune elections later
this year and national elections next year, has been disturbed by
violence for months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
