<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Killed in Renewed Clash in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- At least six Muslim rebels and one
government soldier were killed Tuesday during a renewed fierce
encounter between the two sides in western Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, the military confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
Four soldiers and scores of rebels were wounded in the clash,
the third on Tuesday between Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
guerrillas and government troops in the area, said an officer from
the military's South Command (Southcom) based in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The four-and-half-hour gun battle took place in a village in
Pikit Town, Maguindanao Province, late Tuesday morning, just
several hours after the government troops repulsed a retaliatory
attack by the rebels, Southcom Information Officer Slih Indanan
said.
</P>
<P>
The latest skirmish occurred when elements of the Army's 78th
Infantry Battalion on a security patrol in Kabasayan Village
chanced upon a group of more than 100 heavily-armed MILF men.
</P>
<P>
The troops are now tracking down the fleeing rebels, Indanan
said.
</P>
<P>
On early Tuesday morning, the battalion successfully rescued 43
oil workers captured by the MILF guerrillas, killing eight rebels.
But the rebels later staged a retaliatory attack on the troops,
killing one soldier and wounding four others.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a splinter faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF), is the largest anti-government group in
the country, with an estimated membership of nearly 12,000.
</P>
<P>
The MILF refused to accept a peace deal forged last year by the
MNLF and Manila and began its own peace talks with the government
early this year.
</P>
<P>
But the peace talks, which have been on-and-off due to sporadic
clashes between the two sides, have so far failed to achieve any
substantive progress.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators from the two sides are now conducting their two-day
fifth round of initial peace talks in Cotabato City, capital of
Maguindanao, which is due to end today. A general cease-fire in
the southern Philippines is a major topic for the talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
