<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Urged to Strengthen Internal Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A senior central bank official
today urged Chinese financial institutions to further improve
their internal control mechanism to minimize financial risks.
</P>
<P>
Both domestic and overseas experience in recent years has shown
that an effective internal control system is the first defense
against financial risks, Chen Yuan, deputy governor of the
People's Bank of China, said at a seminar on internal control
within financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The financial crises involving Barings, Daiwa Bank, and
Sumitomo Commercial all had something to do with the
incompleteness and ineffectiveness of an internal control
mechanism, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the recent period of time, Chinese financial institutions
have made unremitting efforts to reinforce internal management and
improve their internal control regime, and as a result their
ability to guard against financial risks has improved, the deputy
governor said.
</P>
<P>
"However, there are still much room for Chinese financial
institutions to improve their internal control system," he said,
adding that some financial institutions have not observed
accounting rules strictly.
</P>
<P>
A lack of internal risk control will result in financial rule
violations and financial crises, Chen warned.
</P>
<P>
The fact that internal control is lax among Chinese financial
institutions has aroused great concern among the whole financial
community and caught the attention of the central government
departments, he said.
</P>
<P>
To make financial institutions improve their internal
risk-control system, the central bank has formulated a series of
measures, such as publishing rules on loans and stepping up
financial supervision, Chen told the seminar, which was attended
by more than 160 Chinese and overseas financial officials and
experts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
