<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Weaker After Second Dow Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
retreated slightly today after Wall Street's second consecutive
pull-back overnight.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate-sensitive banking stocks contributed to the
market's weakness, consolidating after recent strong gains and
affected by lower bond prices amid waning sentiment for a
near-term cut in official interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The leading market indicator, the all ordinaries index, ended
8.3 points down at 2,673.4.
</P>
<P>
"Yesterday the market defied the small fall on the Dow to move
ahead and with the Dow falling again, we had to have a bit of
profit-taking coming in," Intersuisse's Andrew Sekely said.
</P>
<P>
"It was noticeable that the strongest stocks of the last few
days were the ones that have given a bit back."
</P>
<P>
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 11.31
points to 7,760.78, after a 9.95 point fall the previous night.
</P>
<P>
Locally, the banking sector eased 38.9 points to 4,764.9, with
NAB bank losing 20 cents to 18.65 Australian dollars, ANZ bank 15
cents weaker at 9.55 Australian dollars, CBAdown 14 to 15.05
Australian dollars and Westpac off four to 7.75 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the falls were in the banks which of course have moved
ahead so strongly of recent times," Sekely said.
</P>
<P>
The wider all industrials index sank 17 points to 4,177.9, with
Boral 2.35 percent, or 10 cents, lower at 4.15 Australian dollars,
Pacific Dunlop down nine cents to 3.61 Australian dollars, and
Brambles falling 30.6 cents to 25.394 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished 1.2 points softer at 1,517.1,
with BHP easing three to 19.27 Australian dollars, WMC 11 cents
lower at 8.44 Australian dollars and Rio Tinto 3.5 cents up at
23.23 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
QNI today announced it will merge with the nickel division of
South African company Gencor to form the world's fourth largest
producer of nickel.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said it was unclear how the market would react to the
deal.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 0.6 points weaker at 1,528.5, with gold
bullion in Sydney closing at 341.75 US dollars an ounce from
342.20 US dollars last.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totalled 453.44 million shares valued at
984.99 million Australian dollars (738.74 million US dollars) with
falls outnumbering rises by 640 to 521.  
</P>
</TEXT>
