<HEADLINE> China's EximBank to Extend More Preferential Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China's Export-Import Bank
(EximBank) will extend more preferential loans to help promote
cooperation between Chinese and overseas enterprises, according to
sources at a seminar held here today.
</P>
<P>
Practice over the past two years has shown that subsidized
preferential Chinese Government loans not only benefit economic
development in the recipient country, but also enable Chinese
enterprises to tap into overseas markets and compete
internationally, a bank official said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the EximBank will continue to expand its business in
relending subsidized preferential Chinese Government loans, which
are long-term or medium-term loans provided by the Chinese
Government to developing countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government decided to promote the use of
preferential loans as assistance to developing countries in 1995
and designated the EximBank to make the relending.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the EximBank has agreed to relend
preferential loans to 32 projects in 24 countries in Africa, Asia,
Oceania, and Latin America. It has already signed loan agreements
for 15 projects, with the relending amount totaling 1.2 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The EximBank, a policy-oriented bank founded in 1994 to finance
Chinese exports of machinery and electronics, has also signed
general agreements on loans with the governments and relending
institutions of six countries, according to the official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
