<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Involvement in S. Leone's Aborted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria said on Tuesday it did not
sponsor the coup attempt against Sierra Leone's military junta
led by Major Johnny Paul Koroma.
</P>
<P>
The denial was made on the heels of the formal swearing in of
Koroma Tuesday morning as head of state, an event which was held
despite the welter of international condemnation and potential
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Koroma's ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary Council announced
on Monday it foiled a counter coup and arrested about 10 military
officers and politicians allegedly involved in the plot.
</P>
<P>
The military junta also claimed that Nigeria was behind the
aborted coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
But according to Godwin Ugbo, Acting Director of Defence
Information, this was only a "wild allegation" of Koroma's
military regime intended to curry favor from Western countries.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria had no other interest in Sierra Leone than the
restoration of peace and return of power to the civilian
government led by ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, the
defence spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Koroma was reported as saying at his inauguration
ceremony in the military headquarters in the capital Freetown
that the handover of power would lead to chaos in the country.
</P>
<P>
Despite Koroma's promise to establish a broad-based government
made up all parties concerned in an election in due time, his
formal inauguration was seen by observers as a defiance of the
international requirement that the ruling military return power
to the toppled civilian government.
</P>
<P>
According to Ugbo, the west African peacekeeping force, known
as ECOMOG, was still in the course of military build-up while
negotiations for a peaceful settlement of the crisis in the
war-torn country were underway.
</P>
<P>
This, observers said, can be interpreted that if the talks
fail and Koroma continues to refuse a handover of power, ECOMOG
might launch larger scale military intervention to restore
Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG shelled military targets in Freetown shortly after the
military took over power in a coup on May 25, following which
Koroma announced himself to be head of state of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops also exchanged fire with the coupists in an
effort to hold some strategic positions and evacuate foreigners
in the city. The exchange of fire was temporarily stopped when
intensive diplomatic operations started later to seek peaceful
resolution.
</P>
<P>
Beside the threat of imminent attack by ECOMOG, the coupists
have received wide-spread international condemnation even as they
seek to consolidate on their power through shuttling diplomacy in
some African countries to enlist support.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the delegations sent by Koroma regime to
Cote d'Ivoire and Ghana were rebuffed by these countries who
demanded the unconditional restoration of President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
At home, civil servants defied the ruling junta's repeated
order to go back to work, continuing their peaceful strike, while
schools, shops, banks and other service facilities remained
closed.
</P>
<P>
Parliament members and religious leaders have also called on
the junta to return power to civilians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
