<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Financial Reform in Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korean government's efforts to
legalize a controversial financial reform draft are feared to
escalate disputes with labor unions which vowed to use all
possible means to block its passage.
</P>
<P>
Angered at the bills designed to merge the Bank of Korea (BOK),
the Security Supervisory Board (SSB) and the Insurance Supervisory
Board (ISB) into a single supervisory body, labor unions of the
three organizations declared a joint front to stem the
government's action at a press conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the plan to set up the Financial Supervisory Board
(FSB) on Monday, Deputy Prime Minister and Finance and Economy
Minister Kang Kyong-Shik said the BOK will be put merely in charge
of setting monetary and credit policies but be stripped of its
regulatory authority over commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
"The bills run counter to deregulation and citizens' wishes to
get rid of government intervention in the financial sector
following the Hanbo scandal," said Kwon Young-Kil, president of
the Korean Confederation of Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
He said his organization will fight the government attempt of
pushing the bills through.
</P>
<P>
More than one-third of the existing union members in these
bodies are expected to lose their jobs because of the new move.
</P>
<P>
The government has determined to exert all possible efforts to
have the bills passed by the National Assembly as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance and Economy (MOFE) said it is
meaningful that the heads of different organizations reached
agreement on revising the central banking and financial regulatory
systems, putting an end to the controversy that heated up over the
last four decades.
</P>
<P>
"It would be impossible for the parties whose interests
conflict with each other to produce a compromise satisfactory to
all," ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
The presidential office Chongwadae also said that it will push
for the implementation of the reform plan despite strong
opposition from interest groups.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the bills remains unknown as opposition parties
joined unions' efforts to make their passage impossible.
</P>
<P>
The National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and the United
Liberal Democrats (ULD) said the reform "should be made in the
next government," an indication that they would not allow the
current government to score a point through the program, right
before the presidential election scheduled for December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
