<HEADLINE> Code of Conduct Launched in S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A Code of Conduct for Public
Servants has been launched in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Launching the code of conduct in Parliament on Tuesday, South
African Public Service and Administration Minister Zola Skweyiya
called on all public servants to adopt the new code and use it to
eliminate corruption in all its forms, including theft, abuse of
state property and nepotism, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Skweyiya warned that no contravention would be tolerated and
action would be taken in terms of disciplinary provisions
contained in the Public Service Act.
</P>
<P>
The code which has set ethical standards for public servants,
is aimed to stamp out "the litany of incidents of corruption",
improve the work ethic, fight fraud and get public servants to be
honest and helpful, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Among the requirements are a provision that public servants
are expected to serve the public impartially and will not be
allowed to unfairly discriminate against any member of the public
on the grounds of race, gender, ethnic or social origin, age,
religion, political persuasion,and culture or language. 
</P>
</TEXT>
