<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Stronger As Rate Cuts Seen Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
stronger in Sydney today following buying of the unit by offshore
investors on the back of perceptions that any domestic easing in
interest rates was likely to be delayed.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market believed the Reserve Bank of Australia
had missed an opportunity to cut rates following the release last
Thursday of weaker-than-expected employment growth figures.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 75.14 US cents, up from 74.81
US cents at the previous local session close. Yesterday's close
marked the first time in 16 months the unit had been around that
level.
</P>
<P>
"This is probably a corrective move up for the Australian
dollar and we look for possible selling between here and 75.20 US
cents to 75.30 US cents," a trader said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank was seen delaying any policy action until at
least after its July 1 policy meeting. It last cut rates on May
23, lowering the cash rate to 5.5 percent from 6.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 85.35 Japanese yen, up from 84.78
yen previously.
</P>
<P>
It also was at 1.2967 German marks, up from 1.2962.  
</P>
</TEXT>
