<HEADLINE> Nine Pro-reform Rallies Called off in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Nine rallies scheduled this
Saturday for constitutional reforms in various parts of Kenya
have been postponed, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the postponement, opposition Ford-Asili leader
Kenneth Matiba and National Development Party leader Raila Odinga
told a press conference today that the rallies would be
held at a later date.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the scheduled rallies were bound to
provoke a major showdown between the Kenyan government and the
Opposition as the former declared that all the rallies without
licence were illegal and the Kenyan authorities were determined
to crush illegal rallies.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the opposition coalition and some church
groups advocating for constitutional reforms held a rally in
Nairobi which was dispersed by Kenyan police, leading to running
battles in the main streets in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 18 foreign missions accredited to Nairobi Tuesday
urged the Kenyan government and pro-reform organizations to
engage in dialogues to avert violence.
</P>
<P>
Dialogues may facilitate a compromise rather than
confrontation between the two sides, they added.
</P>
<P>
The missions also backed the government's proposed Peaceful
Assemblies Bill to replace the contentious Public Order Act,
saying this was a major step to paving way for the coming General
Elections to be held freely, fairly and peacefully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
