<HEADLINE> S.African Defense Minister Turns Down Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise warned that the proposed military budget
cut could seriously disrupt the defense force's ability to
function and its ability to fight against crime.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Tuesday at the National Council of Provinces (NCOP),
Modise said he found the latest figures for defense budget cuts
alarming.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel had reportedly informed Modise
of a further 700 million Rand (155 million U.S. dollars) cut
which would increase this financial year's cut in the defense
budget to a "staggering "1.4 billion Rand (311 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
"I must say quite frankly that a cut of this order runs the
risk of disrupting the defense function and is creating
tremendous problems for its management," local daily the Citizen
today quoted Modise as saying.
</P>
<P>
The budget cuts, Modise said, would disrupt the military
effort to support the police in the fight against crime, limit
training programs, and result in ending the contracts of a large
number of regular force members, which would increase the number
of unemployment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The disaster-relief ability of the defense force would also
suffer, said Modise, who was engaged in discussions with the
government at the highest level in an attempt to bring home the
consequences of the military budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
Modise has received widespread support from across the
political spectrum in the NCOP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
