<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Leaves for Rome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa this morning left for Rome on a visit to Italy, the first
leg of a European tour that will focus on the European role in
the Mideast scene.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving, Moussa said that he will hold talks with
Italian officials on the developments of the peace process in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, he will head for Paris to join the delegation
accompanying Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on his visit to
France, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will meet with his French counterpart Jacques Chirac
in Paris Thursday to discuss the European role in the peace
process and the settlements issue.
</P>
<P>
After Paris, Moussa said, he will fly to London to discuss with
the new British Labor government Egypt's efforts exerted on the
European arena to salvage the Mideast peace march.
</P>
<P>
Europe has been seeking a stronger role in the Mideast
peacemaking and sent its special envoy to the region several
times in a bid to break the current crisis due to Israel's
construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem
three months ago.
</P>
<P>
In an indication of the futility of Egypt's recent mediation
attempts, Moussa Tuesday ruled out another imminent shuttle tour
by presidential advisor Osama el-Baz to bring closer viewpoints
of the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Gap between the two sides remained despite intensive efforts
to remove obstacles to resuming the deadlocked peace talks, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Baz's several shuttle trips to Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority helped deliver the first meeting in three
months between the two sides in Cairo on June 8. But a second
round of talks was aborted due to remaining rifts.
</P>
<P>
The main obstacle to new substantive talks is the disagreement
over Israeli settlement activity, especially in Arab East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
