<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Finance Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Finance Minister Dan
Meridor resigned after an overnight cabinet meeting on currency
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference following the seven-hour cabinet
meeting, Meridor said he handed a letter of resignation, which
goes into effect in 48 hours, to Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Meridor said he lost confidence in Netanyahu and could no
longer serve in the government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the cabinet, in a vote of 8-3 with 2 abstentions,
rejected the finance minister's opposition to the abolition of
foreign currency exchange controls, which has been supported by
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Meridor said that the abolition, which would lead eventually
to a fully convertible shekel, the Israeli currency, could lead to
a further appreciation of the shekels, and harm the country's
economy, specially the exports.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the economic issues, Tuesday night's cabinet
session was seen as the grand political showdown between Netanyahu
and Meridor, who had been accused of trying to wrest the Likud
nomination from Netanyahu before the elections a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
