<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India May Agree to Five-Year Phase-Out of Import Curbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The final phase-out period for
removal of quantitative restrictions on imports in India is likely
to be five years, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
India's Commerce Ministry has indicated that seven years was
the minimum period required by the country to eliminate import
curbs, yet the offer has already been rejected by both the United
States and the European Union. They have been insisting that
India should have a two-three year schedule to phase out import
curbs.
</P>
<P>
The contrasting stances adopted by India and her major trading
partners at the balance-of-payments consultations at Geneva
earlier this month resulted in the talks being suspended without
any result. The talks, which are being conducted under the
auspices of the World Trade Organization (WTO), will resume on
June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said that India's demand for a seven-year
phase-out period and the developed countries' insistence that this
should be reduced to two or three years are "postures."
Ultimately, the antagonists will compromise on a midway period of
five years.
</P>
<P>
Industry associations like the Confederation of Indian Industry
(CII) have suggested that import curbs should be gradually removed
over five years.
</P>
<P>
India has been reiterating that it is committed to gradually
opening up consumer goods imports, but does not perceive the need
to do so too soon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
