<HEADLINE> Compulsory Education in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China's central government
and the government of Hebei Province have spent nearly 500 million
yuan developing compulsory education in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Most of it has been spent on primary and middle schools in 46
of Hebei's poor counties, and the province has set up 1,600
schools, and provided 106,000 chairs and desks.
</P>
<P>
The province has also spent 25 million yuan buying library
books and teaching equipment.
</P>
<P>
In addition, local education departments have held training
programs to provide further education for teachers in rural
schools.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, all the province will have six-year
compulsory education, fulfilling the objective three years ahead
of time. Meanwhile, ten of the 46 poor counties will have
nine-year compulsory education. 
</P>
