<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Cases Increase in Malaysia's Selangor State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of dengue cases is
increasing in Malaysia's Selangor state which surrounds the
capital city as the water-borne disease is detected in every
district.
</P>
<P>
As of June 17 this year, 2,068 dengue cases and 71 cases of
dengue haemorrhagic fever (DHF) were reported in the state, a 100
percent rise as compared to the same period last year, the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported today, quoting
Selangor Medical and Health Services director Ahmad Shukor Mohd
Noor.
</P>
<P>
Nine people have died of the dengue disease so far this year
and the death rate is quite alarming as compared to 12 for the
whole of last year, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Selangor Health authorities intensified anti-dengue drive to
avert a dengue epidemic in the state, the official said, adding
his department's first task was to identify and destroy aedes
mosquito breeding grounds using a new chemical called "vectovec"
which is found to be very effective.
</P>
<P>
The use of "vectovec" would be restricted to places like
construction sites while a mosquito trap called "ovi trap" would
be used to catch and kill adult mosquitoes, according to the
official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
