<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inter-provincial Harvesting Strong In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 combines and
over 100,000 operators are moving about China's 19 provinces and
autonomous regions as part of inter-regional cooperation in
harvesting this summer's crops.
</P>
<P>
To make the most of China's limited number of farm machines, to
cut labor costs and save on labor, and to avoid grain losses,
ministries and government departments planned earlier this year to
organize trans-regional cooperative use of combines. This method
of harvesting was actually begun by farmers themselves in the
early 1990s, because combine owners didn't have enough land to
work locally.
</P>
<P>
Nie Hongwei, a combine operator from the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region in northwest China, is running a harvester
getting in crops in Yancheng city in central China's Henan
Province. "I will move on to other provinces and autonomous
regions after the harvest is over here, and expect to cut around
166 ha of wheat all summer," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ministries see to it that the provinces and regions share
combines according to different grain maturation dates. They have
also taken steps to provide information and fuel for this
nationwide campaign, and have freed the combines from road fees.
To save time, some of the combines are carried on trucks and
trains.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, governments and farm machinery management
departments began to look for partners elsewhere, and signed
harvest contracts. "More than 300 operators with over 80 combines
in our county rely on contracts," said Liu Zhihong, director of
the farm machinery management department of Qingyuan County in
north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The large-scale inter-province harvesting marks a shift in
Chinese farmers' way of living and production going from
self-sufficiency to prosperity, and the beginning of
market-oriented agricultural mechanization, industry insiders
say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0183 </DOCNO>
