<HEADLINE> Resettlement Project Brings Prosperity To Chinese Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Villagers in a mountainous area
of Northeast China's Liaoning Province have found their life much
improved after they moved out the mountains.
</P>
<P>
Hu Qingji, a former villager in mountainous Liaoyang city, who
moved to another township a year ago, says, "We are living in a
multi-story building, and the whole family earned more than 20,000
yuan last year."
</P>
<P>
Hu is one of 3,500 villagers who have benefited from the
resettlement program that started in 1995 as part of the
nationwide anti-poverty campaign.
</P>
<P>
The project involves the resettlement of 200,000 people in 185
poor mountainous villages with a per-capita annual income below
400 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 80 percent of them have shaken off poverty, and the rest
of them have improved their living and production conditions, say
local government officials.
</P>
<P>
The move has not only given the poor a better life, but also
made it possible to better protect the mountain eco-system,
because villagers used to consume a large number of trees as
firewood.
</P>
<P>
Farmland and forest resources there have become better
utilized. A 533-ha farm is now under construction in the former
Luojia Village.
</P>
<P>
The city will continue with the resettlement program to move
the remaining mountain villagers out by the end of the
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
