<HEADLINE> Minors Well Cared for in Central China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- In view of the rising divorce
rate which left more children poorly treated and educated, central
China's Hunan Province has launched a massive discussion named
"Missing Dad and Mom" to further awaken parents' sense of
responsibility for their children.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the measures taken by the Provincial Committee
on Protecting Minors to improve the environment for the healthy
growth of the young.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up in 1990 as an arm to implement the
country's first law on protecting minors issued in 1988. Similar
committees have also been established in other parts of the
country in which various departments and people from all circles
are involved.
</P>
<P>
The Hunan Provincial Committee on Protecting Minors has in the
past seven years strived to create adequate conditions in
families, schools and the society as a whole for the good of
children.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the discussion, women's federations have opened
classes for parents, teaching them adolescent phsychology,
physiology and education, as well as explaining the law on
protecting minors. 
</P>
