take shape on the western bank of the Taiwan Straits as local
governments are pouring huge funds, estimated to exceed 200
billion yuan by 2005 for basic construction in Meizhou Bay, Fujian
Province.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2005, when construction is completed, the bay will
become a large industrial development zone with port facilities
capable of handling 100 million tons of goods annually.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, Meizhou Bay, which stands midway
between Shanghai and Guangzhou ports, is an ideal place for
building a harbor.
</P>
<P>
The bay covers an area of 643 sq km and has a population of
790,000. The future port city will be divided into two parts for
development, with its southern part focusing on petrochemicals and
the northern part on chemical, processing and tourism industries,
the officials say.
</P>
<P>
A number of port facilities and industrial projects have been
completed or are being constructed in the area, including docks,
railways, expressways and water plants.
</P>
<P>
Now, the southern and northern parts have approved 96
overseas-funded projects involving about 13 billion yuan of
overseas investment, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
Contracts have been signed between local governments and
overseas investors, including some international giants, on
building up a number of big projects. 
</P>
