<HEADLINE> Poland's Economy Grows Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Poland's economy has grown rapidly
in the years since the government of the Democratic Left Alliance
was formed four years ago, Prime Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz
said today.
</P>
<P>
Cimoszewicz told a press conference that since the government
was formed in 1993, the Polish economy has been on a quick
rise. Unemployment and inflation has dropped and wages of workers
and retirement pay have been increased, he said.
</P>
<P>
More and more families are enjoying the economic recovery,
Cimoszewicz added.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Left Alliance, consisting of nearly 30 leftist
political parties, trade unions and other mass organizations, won
the 1993 general elections and became the biggest party in
parliament. It formed the government together with the Polish
Peasant Party.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said over the four years, the gross domestic
product has increased by 26.3 percent, the unemployment rate has
been lowered from 16.9 to 12 percent, the retirement pay increased
by 12 percent and the inflation rate dropped from 50 percent to 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
The export sector registered an annual average increase of 20
percent in the four years, he said, adding that industrial
production increased by 33.5 percent, with the production of small
and medium-sized enterprises up 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the good economic performance to the adoption of
a new constitution, strengthened democracy and domestic
stability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
