<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Finds Little Common Ground in Racial Attitudes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Black Americans and white
Americans share little common ground in their opinions on race
relations, according to a national poll released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The findings reveal that race relations is one of the
foremost problems confronting the U.S.," said Eddie N. Williams,
president of the Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies,
a non-partisan think tank.
</P>
<P>
Williams said the gap in racial attitudes will prove a problem
for national leaders as they prepare to discuss the race issue on
the American agenda.
</P>
<P>
In general, whites viewed race relations in their own
communities as fairly good but saw them as poor in other parts of
the country, according to the poll of 1,702 adults.
</P>
<P>
Blacks saw race relations in their local communities as
similar to those nationally, fair or poor.
</P>
<P>
Whites are considerably more likely than blacks or Hispanics
to describe race relations in their own communities as "excellent"
or "good," said David Bositis, the joint center senior researcher
who conducted the poll.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 50.2 percent of blacks feel there is "a
lot" of discrimination against blacks in America while just 21.1
percent of whites felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
Conducted between March and April this year, the poll surveyed
850 blacks, 850 whites and 100 Hispanics on questions of race
relations, politics and social policy. The margin of error was
plus or minus 4 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Approves Bill to Pay Dues to U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States Senate today
voted 90-5 to pay 819 million U.S. dollars in back dues to the
United Nations, on conditions that reforms are made in the world
body.
</P>
<P>
The payment was in a 12 billion dollar package to fund and
reorganize the State Department.
</P>
<P>
Under the Senate bill, two independent agencies -- the Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency and the U.S. Information Agency --
would be merged into the State Department, and the department
would increase control over the Agency for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
Following the Senate vote, it goes to a conference committee to
work out differences in a version the House passed last week.
</P>
<P>
"It's time to end the long-festering feud between the United
Nations and Washington over our unpaid back dues," said senior
Democrat, Sen. Joseph Biden, of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
Back U.N. dues would be paid over three years. Disputes remain
over exactly what the United States owes for peacekeeping and
other operations and how much would be credited back. But both the
U.S. administration and U.N. officials have praised the compromise
legislation as a big step forward.
</P>
<P>
The Senate bill addresses U.N. arrears, requiring the U.N. to
reduce the share of U.S. dues from 25 percent to 22 percent next
year and 22 percent in fiscal 1999, and reduce the U.S. share for
peace-keeping from 30 percent to 25 percent by 1999.
</P>
<P>
It also asks the U.N. to tighten its budgets and reduce its
staff, open its programs to closer evaluation, ensure U.S. access
to U.N. financial data, and not impose taxes, create a standing
army or encroach on U.S. sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Republican Sen. Richard Lugar, of Indiana, opposed any
conditions on the payment. He said that U.S. support for the world
body was vital to U.S. interests and the future of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
"It makes no sense to deny our allies funds that we owe them,
and expect that they are going to be generous in negotiating
settlements with us in a whole host of agreements around the
globe," said Lugar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
