<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Reach Agreement on Watered-down Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- European Union leaders reached
agreement on a new treaty early Wednesday after watering down
its key contents.
</P>
<P>
"We have reached a complete deal on the content of the treaty
of Amsterdam," Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok, who also serves as
the rotating EU president, announced after the 15 leaders wrapped
up marathon talks shortly before 0130 GMT.
</P>
<P>
"No one can deny that we have today taken a new step towards
European unification," European Commission President Jacques
Santer told a press conference after the conclusion of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, EU heads of state and government, who started their
two-day summit here Monday, watered down many of the proposals
presented by the Dutch EU presidency, and failed to agree to key
institutional reforms to prepare the 15-nation bloc for its
eastward expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
The treaty is designed to modernize the Union as it enters into
the 21st century and prepares to embrace some dozen new members
over the next century.
</P>
<P>
But the leaders failed to reach an accord on the formula of a
new vote distribution in the EU's Council of Ministers, only
agreeing that a decision would be taken just before the
enlargement takes place.
</P>
<P>
Under the new treaty, which will be formally signed in October
in Amsterdam, EU states agree to cooperate more closely in such
areas as asylum, immigration, visa policy and crime fighting, but
the veto remains in the fields of asylum, immigration and refugee
policy because of national sensitivities.
</P>
<P>
The Schengen agreement, which lifts border checks within most
of the EU states, was incorporated into the EU, while allowing
Britain and Ireland, linked to the former through a passport
union, to retain their border checks and the right to set their
own visa, immigration and asylum policy.
</P>
<P>
Denmark's opt-out is a reiteration of a previous one,
reflecting its constitutional problems with passing sovereignty to
EU institutions. However, as a member of the Schengen group, it is
expected to remain part of the border-free zone.
</P>
<P>
On defense, Britain, Denmark and the bloc's neutrals -- Sweden,
Ireland, Finland and Austria -- were resisting calls for
integration of the Western European Union (WEU) defense club into
the bloc, seen by others as a step toward true integration.
</P>
<P>
The language in the text had been toned down, saying only that
the WEU might one day be in the EU.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed that the WEU would remain independent,
sub-contracted to carry out humanitarian, peacekeeping and crisis
management mission for the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
