<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Reforms: From Maastricht to Amsterdam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- It is just over 100 kilometers
from the small town of Maastricht in southeastern Netherlands to
the colorful Dutch capital of Amsterdam. But it has taken the
European Union nearly six years to cover this short distance in
its integration process.
</P>
<P>
After two days of tough negotiations at their mid-year summit
which began on Monday in Amsterdam, EU leaders early on Wednesday
finally reached an agreement on a new EU draft treaty, dubbed the
Amsterdam Treaty, thus concluding the 15-months long
Intergovernmental Conference designed to review the EU's
Maastricht Treaty of December 1991.
</P>
<P>
The revision of the EU treaty is aimed at modernizing the
15-nation bloc as it enters the next century and prepares to
embrace new members from eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok, who also serves as the rotating
EU president, said after the meeting that the Amsterdam summit had
opened the way for the launching of the enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
Within the busy agenda of the two-day summit, unemployment,
which currently affects one in nine EU citizens, was given
unexpected strong emphasis.
</P>
<P>
An employment chapter was inserted into the new treaty,
providing for incentive measures to boost cooperation on
employment between member states.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, leaders lifted the clouds which had surrounded the
first day of the summit by reaching a deal on the Economic and
Monetary Union (EMU) and job creation, resolving a dispute between
France and Germany, the major engine of European integration, on
these two issues.
</P>
<P>
By ratifying the Stability Pact and an employment resolution,
the leaders gave Germany guarantees that rigid budgetary
discipline would be maintained and France received a non-binding
pledge to fight unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Though the EMU-job deal was hailed by all the EU leaders as "a
victory for everyone", the agreed draft Amsterdam treaty is deemed
by many experts as a "modest" and watered-down treaty which falls
short of the high expectations expressed at the start of the
treaty review process.
</P>
<P>
Under the new treaty, which will be signed by EU leaders in
Amsterdam this autumn, the bloc failed to take major steps towards
building a common foreign and defense policy, by only agreeing to
appoint the unknown Eurocrat, instead of a high-level figure
desired by France, to steer EU foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
On defense, EU members only agreed to "foster the institutional
cooperation" between the Western European Union (WEU) defense club
and the bloc. The eventual integration of the WEU into the EU was
blocked by Britain, Denmark and the bloc's neutrals -- Sweden,
Ireland, Finland and Austria.
</P>
<P>
The language in the Treaty was toned down, saying there was
merely a "possibility of integration" of the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
These failures could have lasting consequences in world affairs
and reinforce the United States' pre-eminence in European security
for years to come, an expert said.
</P>
<P>
The Schengen agreement, which lifts border checks within most
of the EU states, has been incorporated into the new treaty, but
allows Britain and Ireland, linked to the former through a
passport union, to retain their border checks and the right to set
their own visa, immigration and asylum policy.
</P>
<P>
The Treaty has postponed, because of unbridgeable differences
between EU's big and small states, a key decision to alter the
balance of power within the Union until the bloc is enlarged to
embrace new members from eastern Europe over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
This has undoubtly cast a serious shadow on the perspective of
the enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Having seen all these setbacks, European citizens will also be
more uncertain about what the "new Citizen's Europe" will look
like by asking the question: "what is the next stop after
Amsterdam?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
