<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Colombo Port Sets Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Colombo Port has set a
record by handling 660,927 TEUs (Twenty Foot Equivalent Units)
during the first five months of this year, a local press report
said today.
</P>
<P>
The total tonnage handled is expected to exceed 1.5 million
TEUs by the end of this year. Last year a total tonnage of one
million TEUs was handled.
</P>
<P>
Colombo port was rated 26th in the world last year as a
container handling port.
</P>
<P>
The report said the volume of cargo handled by the Sri Lanka
Ports Authority grew 20 percent in 1996 compared to an increase of
eight percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The number of vessels that called at the Colombo port increased
by 6 percent to 3,467 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report said the long term objective of the government is to
develop the Colombo port as a hub port in the region and to expand
the Galle port to ease congestion at the Colombo port.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to attract a part of the growing demand for
shipping facilities in the region, said the report, adding that
Proposals are also being studied to develop certain facilities in
the Colombo port.  
</P>
