<P>
KATHMANDU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
demanded that measures be taken to forestall the explosion of
Tsho-Rolpa glacier lake that might come this summer.
</P>
<P>
Recent studies found that the area of the glacier lake,
situated over 4,500 meter high in the Rolwaling Valley about 80
kilometers east of Kathmandu, capital of Nepal, has expanded from
1.37 sq.m. to 1.65 sq.m. and its water volume is estimated at 80
million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said today that the melting process of the
lake, detected in 1996, has sped up along its north-western side.
If it bursts as expected in the summer, 40 million cubic meter of
water will gush out and affect 18 villages along the Rolwaling
river banks including the Khimti Hydro-electricity Project and the
Manthali Airstrip.
</P>
<P>
The Dolakha district administration will hold a meeting on
Thursday to decide on precautionary measures.
</P>
<P>
Experts suggested that villagers living along the river banks
be moved at least 20 meter away during the summer.
</P>
<P>
A siphon is being used as an outlet for the lake water in a bid
to avert the possible disaster, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that even if it does not burst this summer, the
glacier lake could burst next year with even greater effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
