<HEADLINE> Armed Conflict Erupts in Phnom Penh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Two bodyguards of Cambodia's
First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh were killed and an
AFP news agency correspondent was wounded when heavy gunfire and
an explosion shattered the city late last night.
</P>
<P>
In a phone interview earlier today, Ranariddh's security
advisor Srey Kosal told Xinhua that Ranariddh's bodyguards
returned fire when his residence was attacked from a nearby school
by gunmen.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged fire with machine-guns, mortar and
rocket launchers, the advisor said.
</P>
<P>
A curfew was imposed in some areas of the capital and thousands
of soldiers, police and militia units loyal to Prince Norodom
Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC party and Second Prime Minister Hen Sun's
Cambodian People's Party (CPP) were posted around the city.
</P>
<P>
But the gunfire died down around midnight and the city became
calm.
</P>
<P>
A vehicle was destroyed by armed police in front of Xinhua's
Phnom Penh Bureau which is about five hundred meters from
Ranariddh's residence. The driver of the vehicle was wounded.
</P>
<P>
The conflict is being seen as a revenge attack by National
Police Chief Hok Lundy against Ranariddh's bodyguards, who, armed
with rocket launchers, went to Hok's house at 10.30 p.m. (local
time) for the second night in a row to intimidate his bodyguards.
Hok is a member of the CPP.
</P>
<P>
The latest violence is part of the growing political tension in
the country before general elections next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
