<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: "My Confidence in HK Is Growing": Canadian Businessmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- "As the day for Hong Kong's
return to China is at hand, my confidence in future keeps
increasing," said Paul S.K. Lam, president of the Canadian Chamber
of Commerce in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Lam said, "Without living in Hong
Kong, one might not be able to share my positive feelings about
Hong Kong's future."
</P>
<P>
Lam noted Hong Kong's return to China is one of the major
historic events in this century and that it is naturally for the
worldwide news media to focus their attention on it.
</P>
<P>
But he said that he was startled at some pessimistic reports on
Hong Kong's future in his recent business trips to the West.
</P>
<P>
Lam recalled a seminar he attended in the West Palm Beach in
Florida, USA, in April this year at which he found that most of
the audience were mis-presented on what has occurred recently in
Hong Kong as well as the fate of Hong Kong after its return to
China.
</P>
<P>
"At the seminar, I used 30 minutes to brief the American
audience on Hong Kong's past and present situation, from the Opium
War in 1840 to the promulgation of the Sino-British Joint
Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong in 1984, the process of
the selecting Hong Kong's first Chief Executive and the necessity
of the formation of the Provisional Legislative Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I particularly cannot agree with the distorted reports on the
selection of the chief executive of the HKSAR. In my view, these
reports originated from their subjective imaginations and are
contrary to objective reality," he said, adding that they are
unfair toward the HKSAR and its government.
"The fact was that all Hong Kong governors since 1841 have been
appointed by the British government without soliciting opinions
from the people of Hong Kong, whereas the first chief executive of
the HKSAR has been selected by the selection committee that
comprises 400 Hong Kong people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The live-telecast election of the Chief Executive enhanced my
belief in the principle of 'one Country, two Systems' and 'Hong
Kong people ruling Hong Kong'," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lam said that his experiences in the past decade, especially
over the past year, greatly increased his confidence in Hong
Kong's future development.
</P>
<P>
It is beyond any doubt that the Chinese government will keep
its promise in its commitment to Hong Kong, he said. "What the
Chinese government has done in the past 13 years has proved that
it is fully determined to abide by the Sino-British Joint
Declaration as well as the Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
Lam, director and chief executive of New World Insurance, left
Hong Kong for Canada in 1984. Having lived in Canada for four
years, he returned to Hong Kong in 1988 to take up the present
job.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong provides more opportunities in banking
and insurance businesses than Canada does, adding "the simple fact
is that Hong Kong is adjacent to the Chinese interior area where
the economy is growing very rapidly."
</P>
<P>
"But in Canada, things are different," he said, "Canada's
neighbor is the United States whose economy is highly developed
and so it is difficult for businessmen to develop there," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Lam said, the future Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) will continue to provide easy accesses for business
people from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his conviction that the rule of law and free
economy will remain in operation in Hong Kong in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
"As in the past 150-plus years, Hong Kong will continue to be
managed by a corps of civil servants," he said, adding that the
general situation in Hong Kong will be still more stable.
</P>
<P>
Set up in 1976, the Hong Kong-based Canadian Chamber of
Commerce, the largest of its kind outside Canada, has 800 members
among a population of more than 150,000 Canadians engaged in
finance, insurance, accounting, information technology and
telecommunication services in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Lam said that major Canadian firms are regionally headquartered
here and they are using Hong Kong as their base to develop their
business in China's interior area.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by the chamber in April, 99
percent of the respondents said that their companies will be in
Hong Kong beyond the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Most respondents held that China's business environment is
quite favorable and will continue to improve and 85 percent of the
respondents consider the business environment in Hong Kong over
the next two years as either good and very favorable.
</P>
<P>
"My colleagues, too, share the same positive feelings about
Hong Kong's future and for every reason I can say that my
confidence in Hong Kong has a solid base," Lam said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
