<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Debt Hits 109 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bank Indonesia, the central
bank, has urged the private sector to be more prudent in obtaining
foreign loans as the country's total foreign debt soared to 109.3
billion US dollars in March this year.
</P>
<P>
"Both the public and private sectors must be more careful in
obtaining loans. Overseas loans should be used for productive
sectors only," Bank Indonesia governor Soedradjad Djiwandono said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the Bank Indonesia, government debt
totaled 53.3 billion dollars in the 1996/97 fiscal year while
private debt amounted to 56 billion dollars. In the 1995/96 fiscal
year, government debt was 58.6 billion dollars and private debt
was 47.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The decline in government debt was due to the depreciation of
the Japanese yen against the US dollar and early repayment of
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said increased participation of the private
sector in overall economic activity was reflected in the rise of
domestic borrowings from offshore markets.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, economic analyst Professor Anwar Nasution said that
what is important for Indonesia is "how to use the funds."
</P>
<P>
"If the loans are used for non-viable projects, this is
dangerous for the country's economic stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "private sector borrowing is difficult to
control." "Although the central bank has asked the private sector
to report the level of borrowings, this is difficult in practice,"
he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
