<HEADLINE> Improved Assets Evaluation Boosts Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Emerging assets evaluation has
facilitated enterprise reform in north China's Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that local property valuers have
appraised assets worth more than 157.86 billion yuan (21.2 billion
US dollars) in book value so far, which registered an average
increase of more than 30 percent in post-evaluation value.
</P>
<P>
The deepening of the enterprise reform gave rise to a rapid
expansion of asset evaluation agencies and valuers in recent
years, said Chen Jincheng, director of the Provincial
Administration of State Property.
</P>
<P>
For now, there are a total of 74 such agencies and nearly 1,800
professional appraisers in Hebei.
</P>
<P>
According to existing Chinese laws and regulations, state
assets must be appraised for economic activities such as setting
up Sino-overseas joint ventures, asset auctions and transfers,
enterprise mergers, bankruptcies and alliances.  
</P>
</TEXT>
