<HEADLINE> Latvian Premier Denounces Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Latvian premier Andris Skele made a
televised speech on Tuesday evening, saying he was gravely
concerned about the country's political situation in the face of
rising corruption among officials and politicians.
</P>
<P>
He lashed out at several political parties, accusing them of
becoming "clubs and cliques whose highest ideal is to help party
members seek profits and shield them."
</P>
<P>
His speech comes a day after the resignation of Minister of
Culture Rihards Piks who was found to have broken the anti-graft
laws.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Latvian capital Riga said that "a major
political scandal" has been exposed in the country, with 12
government officials and 46 members of parliament having taken up
posts in non-state agencies, violating anti-corruption laws.
</P>
<P>
The scandal indicates that "a new privileged stratum consisted
of special figures" has taken shape in the country, Skele said,
adding that these groups of people have put themselves above the
law.
</P>
<P>
Skele, an entrepreneur without any party affiliation, has been
Latvian Prime Minister since December 1995, following the
country's second general election after independence in 1991. He
heads a coalition government made up of several parties.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Skele sacked his Defense Minister Andrejs Krastins,
accusing him of making fuel deals for the army which violated
state procurement rules.
</P>
<P>
At the time, Skele said fighting corruption had to become one
of the main jobs of the state, and warned that all people
responsible for the use of state funds would be scrutinized very
closely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
