<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ROK Consul General is Confident in Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONGKONG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Yang Chun Park, consul general of
the Republic of Korea (ROK) to Hong Kong, said he is optimistic
about and confident in the future of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is to return to the embrace of China after 156 years
of British rule, he said, "As a friendly neighboring country, ROK
would like to express its sincere congratulations to China on Hong
Kong's return."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government has indicated to the whole world that
Hong Kong's existing social system and lifestyles will remain
unchanged for 50 years after July 1, 1997, he said.
</P>
<P>
"we trust the commitment of the Chinese government. That is why
we are so optimistic about Hong Kong's development and confident
in its future," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Republic Of Korea announced last month it would extend free
entry to passport holders of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region.
</P>
<P>
Referring to economic relations between the ROK and Hong Kong,
Park said that bilateral trade has increased at an annual rate of
10 percent in the past few years. Bilateral trade volume came to
12 billion US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
To date, the ROK has set up 750 companies and 80 financial
institutions in Hong Kong. ROK mainly exports electronic products,
raw materials and plastic products to Hong Kong, while importing
machinery and parts, textiles, watches, electronic and optical
products from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
ROK's investment in Hong Kong is not large, estimated at 339
million US dollars, while Hong Kong's investment in the ROK totals
652 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, Hong Kong is an international trade and
financial center, as well as a gateway to China and to other Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign companies do business via Hong Kong with countries
in Asia and other regions, he said. Last year, ROK's investment
in China exceeded three billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been a popular tourist destination for most ROK
residents. An estimated 400,000 ROK residents visited Hong Kong
last year. The number is expected to reach half a million soon.
</P>
<P>
The ROK has opened an air route from Seoul to Hong Kong, set up
the Korean Resident Association and the Korean Chamber of
Commerce. In 1994, it opened an international school with 372
pupils from 15 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The consul general said that he is not a stranger to Hong Kong
though he assumed his current post in March last year, because he
had stayed here for eight years previously.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the view that the success of Hong Kong lies in the
rule of law, convenient information and clean civil service. All
these factors are combined together to make Hong Kong a very
attractive place for business and tourism.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that after July 1, 1997, ROK investors
will certainly have more opportunities in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baht Hits 14-Year High on Offshore Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The baht Tuesday jumped to a
14-year high against the US dollar as the Thai central bank took
measures to stabilize the baht.
</P>
<P>
The baht was traded as high as 22.90 to the dollar on offshore
markets in the late afternoon, but eased to 23.05 later, according
to reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The baht also rose on the local market as the Bank of Thailand
set its official mid-point rate at 25.77 baht against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank imposed a number of measures to curb
speculation overseas in May and successfully checked the
devaluation trend, but the measures triggered a serious slump on
the local stock market where speculators panically sold stocks to
cash in the baht.
</P>
<P>
The local stock market continued to slip these days. On
Tuesday, the Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell to 497.72
points, the lowest since March 1989.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
