<HEADLINE> Forests Attractive to Chinese Travelers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- About 200 million Chinese
residents, or two among every 13 people, will tour forests as a
new kind of refreshing activity every year by the year 2000,
according to the National Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 60 million Chinese residents and some
200,000 overseas tourists visit forest parks, spending over 500
million yuan (60 million US dollars) each year.
</P>
<P>
More than 780 forest parks have been built across the country,
including 269 national forest parks, such as the well-known
Zhangjiajie park in central China's Hunan Province and Qiandaohu
in east China.
</P>
<P>
Forest tourism took off in the wake of the boom of China's
travel market since the 1980s. After two decades' construction of
infrastructure and accommodation facilities, the forest parks have
become an ideal destination for travelers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
