<HEADLINE> Fugitive Official Accused of Heading Gang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian police are accusing
Vallarino Aleman, the fugitive advisor to Panamanian second Vice
President Felipe Virzi, of being the head of a gang which has
stolen Rolex and Cartier watches for the past four years
</P>
<P>
The advisor travelled frequently to Miami in the United States
to sell watches, stolen in Panama, for about 5,000 U.S. dollars
apiece, Judicial Technical Police Director Alejandro Moncada said
today.
</P>
<P>
Aleman was responsible for providing cover for the thieves by
using a vehicle with Panama's national coat-of-arms, a siren,
flashing lights and radio-communications equipment, the police
chief alleged.
</P>
<P>
Rolex watches are worth between 4,000-25,000 dollars, and
Aleman may be hiding in Costa Rica or the United States, Moncada
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the former advisor's office was "collaborating closely"
in the inquiries that led to the discovery of the felony.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian authorities have requested cooperation by the
International Police (Interpol) in the United States and Costa
Rica in pursuing the fugitive.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, John Barton, a Canadian businessman, was ambushed in a
neighborhood of Panama City and shot to death by a man who stole
his Rolex watch. But Moncada said Aleman's participation in this
particular crime has not been established.
</P>
<P>
The investigations and surveillance of the Rolex-stealing gang
began at least a year ago, and intensified eight months
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
