<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Shortage Seen in Philippines: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- An acute shortage in water and
agricultural supplies is expected to happen in the Philippines in
1997-1998 period due to the El Nino weather phenomenon, the local
press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Scientists at the Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and
Astronomical Services Administration were quoted as saying that El
Nino, a recurring and devastating weather phenomenon in the
Pacific, is affecting the country.
</P>
<P>
The scientists said the delayed onset of the rainy season in
the country was a result of the early development of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
They said the onset of the rainy season, which normally occurs
during the second half of May, was delayed by about two weeks due
to the El Nino episode.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, which appears every two to seven years, is a
large-scale oceanographic and meteorological phenomenon that
develops in the Pacific Ocean. It can cause torrential rains and
storms in South America and drought in Australia, Indonesia and
the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The weathermen warned that assessment of present atmospheric
and oceanographic conditions in the tropical Pacific showed there
is a strong potential for further development of the El Nino
episode in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
They said El Nino could result in drought in the country, which
will lead to shortage in food and water supplies, reduction in the
productivity and other socio-economic problems.
</P>
<P>
Records from the weather bureau showed the worst El
Nino-related drought in the Philippines happened in 1982 and 1990
respectively, both causing big economic losses in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
