<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Makes Progress in Reform of Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The capital of South China's
Guangdong Province has made some progress in reshaping its local
commercial outlets into groups and introducing the modern
enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
The city has created 13 large commercial groups in the past few
years. The groups netted 13.3 billion yuan in business turnover
last year, accounting for about 65 percent of the city's total,
and more than 700 million yuan in gross profits, accounting for 85
percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Some of these groups have started exploring overseas markets,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Restaurant Group is preparing to build a
restaurant chain that will cover Macao, Australia and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The city has taken steps to turn large and medium-sized
enterprises into corporations or joint stock companies in a bid to
optimize the structure of the state assets while giving a free
rein to smaller ones, stressing the flexible operation of the
stock assets.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, 68 of the enterprises trying out the
new system had finished the change-over by the end of March.
</P>
