<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Heat Affects Peruvian Coasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Higher temperatures in Peruvian
coastal waters, with a drop in fish catches and atmospheric
disturbances along the Pacific coastline, are blamed by experts on
the "El Nino" phenomonon.
</P>
<P>
The National Meteorology and Hydrology Service (Senamhi) said
surface water temperatures in the ocean will remain up to 4
degrees C. above normal off Peru's northern and central coasts,
and from 2 to 3 degrees off the southern coasts.
</P>
<P>
The current of warm water that emerged a few weeks ago on the
northern coast has now extended up to 40 miles (74 kilometers)
seawards, where ocean temperatures are 3 degrees C. above normal.
</P>
<P>
In the southern part of the country, the higher temperature of
surface waters is causing disturbances in atmospheric pressure,
mainly in what is known as the Pacific anticyclone.
</P>
<P>
The changes produced by the El Nino phenomenon have begun to
cause damage in some sectors, such as fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The changes in ocean temperatures cause a considerable drop in
the catch of fish species, such as anchovies and sardines which
are essential for the production of fish meal.
</P>
<P>
The scarcity of anchovies along the northern coastline of the
Arequipa department forced the shutdown of the local fish meal
processing plant four days ago.
</P>
<P>
In the northern region of Piura, regional authorities have met
every week to evaluate emergency programs, and to prevent damage
that could be caused by El Nino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
