<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents to Pay for Draining of Tap Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Residents in Chinese cities paying
for their daily supply of water will soon have to pay for the
practice of allowing the water to vanish down the drain, according
to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The move, first introduced in the south China city of Shenzhen,
is aimed at curbing over-consumption and pollution of urban water
resources, the paper cited a central government official as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Residents in the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone have been told
they will have to pay for water drainage beginning August 1.
</P>
<P>
"This has become a necessity and should be enforced as soon as
possible," said Ding Wuhe, a Ministry of Construction official.
</P>
<P>
Ding said that his ministry and the State Planning Commission
have prepared a report for the State Council for approval,
detailing measures on how to collect the fees.
</P>
<P>
The formal approval is expected soon, according to Ding, who
explained that "the practice has actually been stipulated in the
amendment of the Water Pollution Prevention Law, which came into
effect last year."
</P>
<P>
He said the municipal authorities of some local cities,
including the special economic zone of Shenzhen, have worked out
measures on collecting fees.
</P>
<P>
Factories that dispose of large amounts of waste water and
cause water pollution are already being charged in Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Shenzhen practice, drainage charges for water
used by urban families and government organizations account for 30
percent of the costs of tap water.
</P>
<P>
Industrial and commercial departments have to pay drainage fees
that are equivalent to 20 percent of the costs of tap water.
</P>
<P>
The prices of tap water in Chinese cities are usually less than
one yuan per ton.
</P>
<P>
"Such fee-collection standards are not high compared to the
cost of waste water treatment, but considerations should certainly
be given to the economic development levels of different areas in
China so that the fees are acceptable," said Ding.
</P>
<P>
He said funds collected will be used in the construction and
operation of water treatment facilities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Construction indicate that more
than 30 billion cubic meters of waste water is not treated for or
made harmless to human health because of the shortage of funds and
the lack of awareness of environmental protection, according to
Ding.
</P>
<P>
The official said the fees are conducive to water conservation,
an issue troubling most cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said that more than half of the 600 cities
in China are facing a lack of water.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
