<HEADLINE> Spain, Cuba Establish Real Estate Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Cuban authorities and Spanish
businessmen have established a real estate company, the fourth of
its kind involving foreign capital on this Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
The new company, the Costa Habana Inmobiliaria, S.A., will
operate on a 50-50 basis for 10 years in Cuban real estate and its
first project is to build a 175-unit apartment building in
Miramar, a downtown neighborhood in Havana.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the 15 million U.S. dollars project will
begin in the last quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, there were 260 companies operating in Cuba
with foreign investments of 2.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The investments come from about 40 countries, mainly Canada,
Spain, Mexico, Italy, France and Britain, and focus on tourism,
mining, manufacture and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The United States enacted the Helms-Burton Act in March 1996 in
an attempt to frighten away foreign investments in Cuba by
imposing sanctions against companies and businessmen from third
countries who do business with Cuba. 
</P>
