<HEADLINE> German Defense Minister Says NATO Will Continue to Expand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 17 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Volker
Ruehe said here today NATO's door will remain open to all those
willing to get in although only three countries will be invited
to the special summit in Madrid in July.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe said after his two-day visit to Finland that in NATO's
first stage of development, Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic
are expected to be invited to join, but in the future more
countries would be invited by the alliance.
</P>
<P>
He said it is very possible for Slovenia and Romania to be the
fourth or fifth to join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe added that it is up to Finland itself to decide whether
to join NATO, for first there has to be a willingness to join.
</P>
<P>
The German defense minister went on to say that NATO-Russia
relationship is now on the right track. The two sides have pledged
to develop a stable security partnership, not to use force or
threaten with force and to brief each other on defense policies
and military theories.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe, who arrived here Monday, had held talks with his Finnish
counterpart Anneli Taina on security situation in Europe and other
issues of mutual concern. 
</P>
