today in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
The event will end on Sunday, June 22. Telescopes and
astronomical satellites in education and research are being
displayed and a number of world experts and scholares have been
invited to attend this morning the inauguration of the
astronomical observatory "Suyapa", the biggest in Central America.
</P>
<P>
During the opening ceremony, Honduran President Carlos
Roberto Reina said that Honduras is trying to move ahead in
search of its destiny and to close the immense gap between the
most and least developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The president explained that "very few times in Tegucigalpa, an
old city with a colonial and indigenous atmosphere, we see
citizens from Australia, Holland, India, Morroco, Zambia and many
other countries, such as the ones that are now accompanying us
during this important workshop on space.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is taking place in the reception rooms of the
Foreign Ministry and the incorporation of basic space science
vis-a-vis the XXI century as well as astronomical education and
research in Central America will be tackled, among other topics.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Adriana Ocampo, a scientist for the U.S.
National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) announced
that the view of the first landing of an unmanned spaceship on the
planet Mars will be able to be seen in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
The landing of the Mars pathfinder spaceship is expected to
occur at 17:00 hours (local time) this July 4th and will be seen
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
According to the scientist, the explorations that the spaceship
will explore the surface of Mars to clarify whether life exists on
the planet or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
