<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armed Patrolmen Protect Animals in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The local government of southwest
China's Yunnan Province has formed a team of armed patrolmen to
protect the tropical rainforest and rare wild animals in
Xishuangbanna, a national nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
The team members, dominated by armed police and employees at
the reserve, have caught 22 poachers and confiscated 18 hunting
rifles over the past ten days.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they investigated some 80 restaurants in the area
and punished some owners who illegally sell meat of wild
animals. They have rescued many rare animals and returned them to
the forest.
</P>
<P>
Xishuangbanna in southwest Yunnan earned its reputation as "a
kingdom of plants and animals" for its more than 20,000 species of
plants, 429 species of birds and 67 species of animals in over
466,000 hectares of rainforest.
</P>
<P>
However, poaching and illegal lumbering have endangered the
precious natural resources, causing millions in economic losses
annually.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan's legislative body has enacted a series of laws on the
protection of wild animals and plants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
