<HEADLINE> Macedonia Asks NATO Stay in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian President Kiro
Gligorov today asked the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
peacekeeping forces stay on in Bosnia beyond their stated
departure time.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with United States President Bill
Clinton, Gligorov told reporters that some or all of the
peacekeeping troops could stay in his country.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has decided to pull out all its troops by June 1998,
and the Europeans said they would do the same.
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that the presence of the peace (keeping)
forces has greatly contributed to settling the issue and ending
the senseless war there," Gligorov said.
</P>
<P>
"It ended the killings of the people. It ended ethnic
cleansing. And therefore I believe that their remaining on the
Balkans and in this region, where Macedonia is also located, would
be very positive," he added.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Michael McCurry said the two presidents
focused on keeping stability and peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Clinton expressed continuing U.S. support for the stability of
the former Yugoslav republic of Macedonia and the region as a
whole, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
