<HEADLINE> Deutsche Bank Helps Raise Panda in Sichuan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Deutsche Bank AG, Europe's
biggest bank, has agreed to fund the raising of a panda in the
Wolong Nature Reserve in Southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
For one year, the bank will cover the costs of bringing up the
2.5-year-old male giant panda, according to Johannes Schoeter, who
is in charge of the bank's China operation.
</P>
<P>
China's giant panda is a treasure of mankind, Mr. Schoeter
said. And his bank would like to make its due contributions to the
protection and research of the rare animal.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Harner, head of the bank's representative office in
Shanghai, said that the bank is considering developing broader
ties with China, not only in large cities like Beijing and
Shanghai and some coastal areas, but also in China's interior
areas.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bank plans to open a branch in Shanghai and
hopes to invest in several other projects in Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
China is the only natural home of giant panda. It is estimated
that there are only 1,000 giant pandas living in the wild and
captivity.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Chinese scientists have made marked progress
in artificial breeding of giant pandas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
