<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Marks World Anti-Desertification Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 10,000 people in
northeast China's Liaoning Province have joined in a signature
activity to support the country's fight against desertification.
</P>
<P>
The activity on Tuesday was part of a nationwide campaign,
which involved over one million people, to mark the World Day to
Combat Desertification and Drought.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is one of China's provinces challenged by serious
problems of desertification and drought. About 43,000 square
kilometers of land area in its western part have turned into
desert, accounting for 30 percent of its total land area.
</P>
<P>
Forestry, water conservation and agricultural authorities of
Liaoning have mobilized local people to carry out
desertification-control work in the past years, such as planting
trees to form shelter-forests and control soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
In China, more than 2.6 million sq.km. of land area has been
affected by desertification, accounting for 27.3 percent of the
total, according to Minister of Forestry Xu Youfang.
</P>
<P>
The country's direct economic loss caused by desertification
has reached about 54 billion yuan (6.5 billion US dollars) each
year, he said in Beijing Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
