<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes Re-opening of Pak-India Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The British government welcomes
the recent re-opening of dialogue between Pakistan and India, said
visiting British Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth
Affairs Derek Fatchett.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said in a news release that Britain could play a role
in resolving the Kashmir dispute if desired by Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
"We in Britain welcome the dialogue that has recommenced
between Pakistan and India," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett hoped that the recent initiatives of Pakistan's Prime
Ministers Nawaz Sharif and his Indian counterpart Inder K. Gujral
will soon bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
"I have also repeated our offer of our good offices if that
will assist the talks and it is wished by the parties," said
Fatchett.
</P>
<P>
However, Fatchett said, the British offer in no way undermines
her view that talks between the two Governments offer the "best
way of resolving all the problems between India and Pakistan,
including Kashmir".
</P>
<P>
He supported the efforts of the U.N. Special Mission in
Afghanistan. "We look to Pakistan to use its influence with the
warring parties in favor of a negotiated solution under U.N.
auspices."
</P>
<P>
Britain, Fatchett said, recognized that Pakistan had suffered
from the continuing conflict in Afghanistan and stood to benefit
from a peaceful resolution.
</P>
<P>
The British Foreign Minister lauded commitment by the Pakistani
Government to democracy and the rule of law. "We attach the
greatest importance to the proper and safe guarding of human
rights and fundamental freedoms in Pakistan," he added.
</P>
<P>
Britain has been the largest foreign investor in Pakistan this
year and last. It is also one of Pakistan's biggest trading
partners, and one of its largest aid donors.
</P>
<P>
The new British Government, Fatchett said, was keen to build on
that firm base. "Britain already cooperates closely with Pakistan
in trying to combat the drugs trade which menaces both our
societies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett is here on a three-day official visit to Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
