<HEADLINE> Pak, UK to Further Enhance Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif and visiting British Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs
Derek Fatchett have agreed to further explore ways and means to
enhance cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sharif and Fatchett, who is on a 3-day visit to Pakistan,
discussed regional and international issues of mutual concern
during their meeting late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett, the first high official from Britain to Pakistan
after the formation of the Labor government, said that his
engagements in Pakistan have been extremely useful in providing
him first hand knowledge of the country and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming the ongoing dialogue between Pakistan and
India, he hoped that the two countries will be able to resolve all
issues including the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani Prime Minister informed Fatchett about the
efforts of his government to engage in a structured dialogue with
India to tackle all bilateral issues including Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Briefing Fatchett about the political and economic policies of
his government, Sharif said that the far reaching measures adopted
in the last few months would enable Pakistan to become a vibrant
and democratic country with a prosperous economy.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan,
who will visit London in July as his special envoy, will further
explore ways and means to enhance cooperation and linkages between
Pakistan and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Britain has been the largest investor in Pakistan in the past
two years and it is also one of largest trade partners of
Pakistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
