<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Leaders Agree to Postpone Decision on Voting System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- European Union leaders,
struggling into the night on Tuesday towards finalizing the new
draft EU treaty, agreed to postpone a key decision on
institutional reform until the Union is enlarged to embrace new
members from eastern Europe in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after a deadlock between big countries
seeking more votes to enforce their influence, and small states
opposing the proposed pro-big-states voting system revision,
fearing losing already limited voices in Union affairs.
</P>
<P>
"There is an agreement on the institution, in the sense that
they (member states) will decide what to do at the moment of
enlargement," a senior EU official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The accord reached shortly before midnight on the second day of
a EU summit designed to adopt a new EU treaty as the 15-nation
bloc enters into the 21st century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
