<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Affirmative Action Programs under Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers in both House of
Representatives and Senate of the United States are preparing a
push to end racial or gender preferences in government hiring,
contracting and other practices.
</P>
<P>
The effort comes three days after President Bill Clinton
outlined his goal to narrow racial divides plaguing the nation,
splits that affirmative action programs were designed to heal.
</P>
<P>
Senator Mitch McConnell, Republican from Kentucky, who is
leading the effort in the Senate, called it "the next step in our
nation's struggle to overcome discrimination."
</P>
<P>
McConnell is planning legislation similar to a bill Florida
Republican Representative Charles Canady introduced today to end
racial or gender preferences in government hiring, contracting and
other practices.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton favors affirmative action programs to help
women and minorities. Those programs sprang from the civil rights
movement three decades ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
