<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Committee to Celebrate Return of Hong Kong Announces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 17 (Xinhua) --Thousands of Chinese-Americans
will parade down Broadway on July 6 in a colorful celebration of
ethnic pride to welcome the return of Hong Kong to the motherland
and the end of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
This was formally announced today to American and Chinese media
at a news conference organized by the Committee to Celebrate the
Return of Hong Kong at the statue of Confucius in the heart of
Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
The parade, the first-ever Chinese Cultural Heritage Parade in
New york City that takes the celebration beyond the borders of
Chinatown, will consist of more than 100 organizations from the
greater New York metropolitan area and will include an 85-foot
dragon, 20 floats, 3 marching bands and 7 dance troupes. One of
the highlights of the event will be a Beijing Opera troupe which
will perform an entire Chinese opera while parading down Broadway.
</P>
<P>
"As this parade is to take place two days after America's
Independence Day and six days after the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland after a century-and-half of British colonial rule, it
will be a double celebration," said Charles P. Wang, executive
director of the Committee to Celebrate the Return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to share with our fellow Americans the richness
and diversity of our culture," Wang added.
</P>
<P>
Kai Sing Wong, chairman of the Committee to Celebrate the
Return of Hong Kong, said that Chinese-Americans view the return
of Hong Kong "as a celebration to welcome the end of colonialism
and the righting of an historical wrong."
</P>
<P>
He urged all Americans, as well as many immigrant groups to
gather along the parade route and join with Chinese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
It was also announced at today's news conference that there
would also be a Chinatown parade on June 30 that kicks off the
week-long celebration of the return of Hong Kong. On July 3, there
will be a gala concert at Lincoln Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
