<HEADLINE> Albright Visits Cambodia as Planned Despite Gunfire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright will not change her plan of next week's visit to Cambodia
despite of gunfire in the capital of Phnom Penh, State Department
spokesman Nicholas Burns said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is no change in the plans. She plans to visit Hanoi and
Ho Chi Minh City and Phnom Penh next week before she goes into
Hong Kong for reversion," Burns told reporters at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
Reports said conflict between the two prime ministers of
Cambodia broke out on Tuesday with gun and mortar fire echoing
through the capital.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador Kenneth Quinn said a mortar round crashed into
the front yard of his residence, shattering its windows.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the United States will be watching this situation
"very closely". "We have an important embassy there. They're on
the spot," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
