<HEADLINE> U.S. Navy Subs New Communication Strategy Called </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. submarine fleet is in
danger of operational irrelevance if it does not embrace a new
communication system strategy, several U.S. Navy admirals warned.
</P>
<P>
Today, operations dictate that submarines operate closer to
enemy shores, remain in constant communication with battle group
and theater commanders and have the requisite systems to instantly
communicate intelligence data gleaned from offshore reconnaissance
to national leaders, the Defense News said in its latest edition.
</P>
<P>
However, the submarine force does not have those systems today,
and the service may not be earmarking the right systems to perform
those missions in the New Attack Submarine either, the admirals
warned.
</P>
<P>
"The submarine force is marginally equipped today in terms of
communications connectivity," said Rear Adm. Robert Frick, in a
June 5 presentation to the Naval Submarine League's annual
symposium in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we undertake some dynamic changes in command, control,
communications, computers and intelligence, we are not going to be
a player," Frick said.
</P>
<P>
The admirals called for more fundings to upgrade the systems on
the submarines.
</P>
<P>
Key systems the sub force is seeking to deploy on current and
future submarines include more satellite antennas, which will
increase the amount of data submarines can transmit and receive;
development of a fully automated radio room; and information
processing systems that will speed data the submarine can process
simultaneously, the News said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
