<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clarke Tops Tory Leadership Second Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Former Chancellor Kenneth Clarke
topped the second round of the Tory leadership contest today with
64 votes.
</P>
<P>
The other two contenders, William Hague, former Welsh Secretary
and John Redwood, former cabinet minister, polled 62 and 38 votes
respectively.
</P>
<P>
There was no outright winner as Clarke failed to secure the 83
votes needed to be elected leader.
</P>
<P>
But Clarke's backers were confident their man would pick up
enough votes from the Redwood camp to carry him to victory.
</P>
<P>
"I think today is an extremely encouraging result. I'm glad
we're now in the final furlong, but I think we're obviously going
to win," Clarke said.
</P>
<P>
He accused Hague of changing his position several times before
finally demanding that any MPs who wanted to serve in his
"shadow" cabinet must declare their opposition to scrapping the
pound.
</P>
<P>
"I'm well satisfied with the results of the second ballot
... I think I now have the momentum and the support to win the
third ballot on Thursday," said Hague, who at 36 would be the
youngest Conservative leader in more than 200 years, if he wins
the contest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
