<HEADLINE> U.S. Concerned over Turkish Exercises Near Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday
expressed concerns over reports of Turkish military exercises near
the island of Cyprus and asked Ankara to explain its actions.
</P>
<P>
"We 're very concerned about the reports of the movement of
Turkish naval vessels," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns
told reporters. "The United States, frankly, does not know the
reasons behind these reported military naval maneuvers."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government on Tuesday lodged a complaint with the
United Nations, claiming 16 Turkish jets had overflown the
Turkish-occupied northern part of the divided island. It also said
warships had docked at the ports of Famagusta and Kyrenia in that
region.
</P>
<P>
Turkish press reports said two frigates, three submarines, one
destroyer and three missile boats were involved.
</P>
<P>
"We think it's very important that all the parties involved in
trying to resolve the Cyprus dispute, not take any unilateral
measures that would disrupt in any way the United
Nations-sponsored peace talks," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
The island has been divided since Turkey invaded the northern
third of the island in July 1974 to protect the Turkish Cypriot
minority in the wake of an abortive coup by supporters of union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Talks aimed at resolving the crisis are scheduled to begin
next month at the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
