<HEADLINE> Bonn to Plug Budget Hole With 23 Bln Marks From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The German government is planning to
pump about 23 billion German marks (about 13 billion U.S. dollars)
from privatization of state enterprises to help plug huge holes in
its budgets for 1997 and 1998, a German newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The widely circulated newspaper Bild quoted reliable sources in
the German Finance Ministry as saying that Finance Minister Theo
Waigel is expecting about 6.3 billion marks (about 3.56 billion
dollars) this year from partly selling off the government's stakes
in the Postbank, the German airliner Lufthansa and the
construction company Deutschbau.
</P>
<P>
Another about 17 billion marks (about 9.6 billion dollars) is
about to be generated in 1998 from the privatization of the
telecommunications company Deutsche Telecom and sales of state
house property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
