<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation in Northeastern Angola Still Tense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The UN Angola Verification Mission
(UNAVEM) issued a communique here today declaring that the
situation in northeastern Angola is "still tense".
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the 16-member UNAVEM, headed by
Commander Philip Sibanda, heard "tense gunfire" in the Luia area,
Lundanorte Province in northeastern Angola when they reached
there yesterday, but failed to find the cause for the gunfire.
</P>
<P>
It said some of the UNAVEM members were harassed by men from
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The UNITA interpreted this as a protest against the UN mission's
statement made on June 14 stressing that "there was no conflict
in Lundanorte Province."
</P>
<P>
In fact, the UN mission said that the situation there was
"quiet", and there was no sign of battles between government
troops and UNITA forces.
</P>
<P>
Situation in northeastern Angola has become tense in the past
days after government troops and UNITA forces opened fire at
each other for several times.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Commission Overseeing the Peace Process in Angola, a
group made of members from the UN peace mission, the Angolan
government and UNITA, is scheduled to hold a meeting to discuss
the situation in northeastern Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
