<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President-Elect Meets Pakistani PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President-elect Mohammad
Khatami met today with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, who
arrived here Monday for talks with Iranian leaders on the Afghan
crisis.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time for the 54-year-old new president to
meet foreign guests since he won a landslide victory in the
presidential election on May 23.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, who will take over power from outgoing President
Hashemi Rafsanjani in August, said Iran is interested in
reinforcing relations with other countries, especially with the
regional states.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that peace and security are prerequisites for
development of the region, and solid relations between Iran and
Pakistan which share a common border and access to the Indian
Ocean would serve to consolidate peace and stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Afghan crisis, he termed the living
conditions of the Afghan people as "deplorable."
</P>
<P>
The Islamic and historical mission of the two neighboring
countries of Iran and Pakistan require them, as well as other
regional states, to encourage the warring parties to hold peace
talks and reach a logical settlement, Khatami added.
</P>
<P>
On Pakistan-India dispute over Kashmir, Khatami expressed hope
that the current negotiations between the two countries would
serve to normalize Islamabad-New Delhi relations, and trilateral
relations would be formed among Iran, Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nawaz Sharif said Pakistan has special relations
with Iran and the new Pakistani government has based its diplomacy
on further strengthening ties with the Muslim neighbor.
</P>
<P>
On the Afghan crisis, Sharif said Pakistan believes that the
Afghan crisis has no military solution and the rival factions
should reach settlement at the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Sharif invited Khatami to visit Islamabad after taking office
in August.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is widely believed to have given financial and
military backing to the Taliban Islamic militia, a faction that
captured the Afghan capital of Kabul in September and took control
of two-thirds of the country.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was also the first country to recognize the Taliban
government.
</P>
<P>
Taliban repeatedly accused Iran of supporting the ousted
government of President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Iran has denied giving military assistance to any of the Afghan
factions, saying it had sent only humanitarian aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
