<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Erekat Criticizes Netanyahu's Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
today accused Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu of giving
the "green light" to settlement activities throughout the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Israel Radio, top Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat said Netanyahu apparently allowed Jewish
settlers "to do something everyday, somewhere," in expanding
settlements.
</P>
<P>
Erekat expressed his hope that Netanyahu would understand his
settlement policy was "shutting down" the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
hinted today that Egyptian shuttle diplomacy between Israel and
the Palestinians would come to a stop.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, Moussa said that there was "no discussion" in bringing
back presidential adviser Osama el-Baz for further consultation
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process is going through a huge crisis," said the
Egyptian foreign minister. "A huge gap still exists (between
Israel and the Palestinians)."
</P>
<P>
In the last few weeks, el-Baz held a series of talks with
Netanyahu and Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat, in
an effort to bring the two sides back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
However, his shuttle diplomacy apparently failed in making any
real progress, as violent confrontations between Israeli soldiers
and the Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip continued
for the fourth consecutive day today.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said that the Palestinians were willing to support the
Egyptian effort in helping the two sides to resume peace talks,
but he stressed that the Jewish settlement activity was a big
obstacle.
</P>
<P>
"We should agree openly only to solve our problems through
negotiations, not through terror, not through bulldozers (to
expand settlements), not through confiscating land, and not
through settlements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians have been
stalled since March when Israel started to build a controversial
new Jewish neighborhood at Har Homa (Jabal Abu Ghneim) on the
southeastern outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have said that Israel must stop the construction
before talks can resume, while Israel insists that the Palestinian
National Authority must crack down on terror and re-establish full
security cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
