<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Signing of New EU Treaty Expected in Autumn: Dutch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, June 17 (Xinhua) -- If the draft new EU treaty --
the Amsterdam Treaty -- is agreed by the European Union leaders
today, it will be signed in autumn this year, said Dutch
officials.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Dutch Foreign Ministry said that the Dutch
EU presidency was considering a date "between mid-September and
mid-October." The signing ceremony will be taken place in
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
The new treaty will come into force only after being ratified
by all national parliaments of the 15 EU member states. The
process is expected to take one and half to two years.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders, meeting on the second day in Amsterdam for
their two-day summit, are now struggling during their negotiations
to settle the last sticking points for the new Union treaty aimed
to modernize the bloc as it enters the next century and prepare to
embrace new members from Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats said the negotiations were running behind schedule
and some delegations warned that the talks could run well into
late evening. 
</P>
