<HEADLINE> Minister: Iraq Concerns over UNSCOM's Missions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has expressed its serious
concerns over the missions of the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM), the official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed Monday to the U.N. Security Council
President Sergev Lavrov, Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
said the UNSCOM's missions were meant to "take advantage of the
facilities available as a cover to gain access to Iraq's security
systems" rather than to carry out the commission's tasks defined
by relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that his country's concerns stem from the fact
that many of those entrusted with the inspection mission are
Americans recruited for the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The repeated inquiries by Colonel Scott Ritter, a former U.S.
chief inspector, to inspect some sites are aimed to achieve other
goals "irrelevant" to the Security Council resolutions, Aziz
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has reportedly blocked U.N. inspectors from three
suspected weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
Azia strongly criticized "a particularly well-known state,"
saying its real aim behind the inspection is to "keep matters
pending and consequently maintain the embargo indefinitely."
</P>
<P>
Iraq is required to allow U.N. inspectors into any site they
choose to ensure its compliance with U.N. resolutions. The
six-year-old U.N. sanctions will not be lift until the inspectors
confirm Iraq has scrapped weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
