<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-17 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Issue Crucial to Cyprus Solution: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides stressed here today that the security issue is crucial
to a solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks upon his return from official
visits to Japan and Russia. His visits came a month before the
U.N.-sponsored direct talks between Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, scheduled to
begin on July 9 near New York.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his Moscow trip, where he met his Russian
counterpart Yevgeni Primakov, Kasoulides said that security, an
issue he described as "dominant and an integral part of a Cyprus
solution", was part of his discussions in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The purchase of Russian anti-aircraft missiles by the Cypriot
government should not be isolated for discussion during the next
month's direct talks, Kasoulides pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He added that "the deployment of the Russian S-300 missiles in
Cyprus would be a negative development, but the presence of
Turkish occupation troops in Cyprus is an even more negative
development."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Russia have come under fire from the U.S., British
and other foreign governments after a multi-million dollar arms
deal for the purchase of the missiles was announced earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has stressed that the purchase of the
missiles is purely for defensive purposes and has also reassured
anxious foreign governments that no missile component will be
delivered in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
On Russia's role in the forthcoming direct talks, Kasoulides
said Russia intends to play the role which all permanent members
of the Security Council are expected to play.
</P>
<P>
Outlining possible areas of "give and take" in the forthcoming
talks, Kasoulides said "the Greek Cypriot side is ready to give
political equality to the Turkish Cypriot side, as this is defined
by the U.N."
</P>
<P>
"When it comes to 'take', we consider the withdrawal of
Turkish occupation troops and the safeguard of fundamental
freedoms should be included in the list of takings," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides was critical of suggestions that some 5,000 Turkish
troops could remain on the island after a solution to the Cyprus
problem is concluded.
</P>
<P>
"The presence of 5,000 Turkish troops may create a feeling of
security for the Turkish Cypriots but it creates exactly the
opposite feeling among the Greek Cypriots," Kasoulides explained.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took control of 37 percent of the island in the wake
of a short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Around 30,000 Turkish troops has been stationed in northern
Cyprus, which was declared as a breakaway state "The Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" by the Turkish Cypriot side in
1983. The entity is recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
