<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Optimistic of S. Africa's Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign banks operating in
South Africa are optimistic about doing business in the country
and expecting strong growth potential from the further relaxation
of exchange controls, according to a survey released here today.
</P>
<P>
A statement by Price Waterhouse, the company which conducted
the survey, said foreign banks doing business in South Africa
were optimistic about future opportunities in the local market,
noting 31 of the 70 foreign banks with a presence in South Africa
participated in the survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicated that the participating banks employed
1,101 people, and projected a 73 percent rise in employment over
next five years.
</P>
<P>
The banks' loan portfolio amounted to 5.45 billion US Dollars
at present and was expected to grow to around 9 billion US
Dollars by the year 2001, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The survey also said the banks believed the lifting of
exchange controls was the single biggest change that would occur
in the local market, while other important considerations were
the proliferation of competitors, the likelihood of a shake-out
and the opportunities expected to arise from privatization.
</P>
<P>
The problem facing the companies was the lack of skilled local
personnel, which was exacerbated by the possibility of losing
staff to other banks, said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
