<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign to Downlist African Elephant Lost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The three southern African
neighbors tonight lost their bid to have the elephant downlisted
from Appendix I to Appendix II of the Convention on International
Trade in Endangered Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe proposed that the African
elephant be downlisted from the CITES Appendix I to Appendix II,
which would allow for limited and controlled trade in the
elephant and its products.
</P>
<P>
It requires at least two thirds of the number of voting
parties to get the proposal through.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 124 registered voting parties, some 123 cast
ballots, of which 75 were in favor of downlisting with some
conditions, 41 polled against while there were seven abstentions.
</P>
<P>
During debate ahead of voting, it had become apparent that
more countries were in support of sustainable use of natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
Opposers of the downlisting proposal were mainly developed
countries and a number of African countries.
</P>
<P>
Countries from the Middle East, Asia, Latin America and North
Africa came out in full support of the downlisting.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Environment and Tourism Minister Chen
Chimutengwende said, "in Tokyo, Japan in 1989, we got eight votes
and this time we got 75 votes, short of majority by only three."
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the conference and Zimbabwe's ambassador to the
United Nations and Geneva Jichaona Jokonya said, "this is a
victory for us. It shows that our argument is sensible and many
people are realizing that they are not guided by any sense of
objectivity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Government to Target Debt Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government will focus
on reducing its total debt burden once the annual deficit is
eliminated, Financial Minister Paul Martin has said.
</P>
<P>
As it does so, the federal government will spend in critical
areas to encourage economic growth, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
"As long as you are piling up debt, which is what the deficit
is about, you have to focus on the elimination of the deficit by
reducing spending," Martin was quoted by reports today as saying.
</P>
<P>
While the government plans to eliminate the deficit in two
years, many analysts believe that it could balance the federal
books as early as next year.
</P>
<P>
Despite this better-than-expected performance, Martin said his
government will not give in to pressure for big spending increases
or tax cuts before the budget is balanced.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Canada must reduce its level of debt, measured as
a percentage of the gross domestic product (GDP), Martin stressed.
</P>
<P>
At present, Canada's federal debt is about 430 billion U.S.
dollars, or 74 percent of its GDP. That's the highest in the G-7
countries, second only to Italy.
</P>
<P>
With so heavy a debt, the government pays 33 cents in interest
charges for every 1 dollar in revenue it raises as a result.
</P>
<P>
The government is committed to reducing the debt-to-GDP level
well below 60 percent within a few years, Martin said. He didn't
set targets for progress.
</P>
<P>
"You don't borrow to cut taxes and you don't borrow to spend,"
he said. "That's what got us into trouble in the first place."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
