<HEADLINE> U.S. Officials to Study Cruise Missile Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Pentagon officials have decided
to study ways to combat possible cruise missile strike against the
United States, Defense News said.
</P>
<P>
The Ballistic Missile Defense Organization (BMDO), Joint
Theater Air and Missile Defense Organization and the Atlantic
Command are planning to set up an integrated product team to study
the threats and ways to counter them, Air Force Lt. Col. Rick
Lehner, BMDO spokesman was quoted as saying last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
BMDO plans to spend about 12 million U.S. dollars in 1998
studying defenses against cruise missiles for military theaters
abroad and the United States, Air Force Lt. Gen. Lester Lyles,
director of the organization told a meeting of the Defense Writers
Group her on June 5, the News said in its June 16-22 edition.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon also promised in its Quadrennial Defense Review report
on May 19 to devote more attention to cruise missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
Cruise missiles, such as the U.S. Tomahawk, are akin to
low-flying pilotless planes. They are hard to detect amid the
radar clutter of the ground and can be preprogrammed to strike
with pinpoint accuracy.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon officials said that the availability of Global
Positioning System receivers and jet engines that can be used on
airplanes or missiles make cruise missiles a growing threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
