<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy to Show Strong Growth, Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian economy will be the
leader among the G-7 industrialized countries this year and next,
economists at one of the largest Canadian bank predicted today.
</P>
<P>
"We are now reaping the full rewards of low interest rates,"
said Ruth Getter, senior vice president and chief economist at
Toronto Dominion Bank.
</P>
<P>
Following years of deficit-cutting, Canada now boasts a
much-reduced government budget deficit, a current account surplus
and a low inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
Canadian short-term interest rates are the lowest they have
been in about 40 years, and remained about 2 percentage points
below comparable U.S interest rates since 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook for the Canadian economy is the best it has been
in this decade," Getter said.
</P>
<P>
"We have gone through a long period of retrenchment and
adjustment, and we are now able to enjoy the benefits."
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, Canada's real gross domestic product
will grow at 3.5 percent this year and 3.2 percent next year,
leading the G-7 nations.
</P>
<P>
Its unemployment rate, at 9.5 percent in May, will ease to 9.4
this year and 9.0 next year, with the addition of 300,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Alberta is forecast to be the top performer among Canada's
provincial economies this year, followed closely by Ontario and
Manitoba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
