<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Rejects Unconditional Payment of UN Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today
overwhelmingly rejected an unconditional proposal to pay all its
United Nations arrears.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was raised by Senator Richard Lugar, who insists
that U.S. support for the world body is vital to U.S. interests
and the future of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Lugar's unconditional proposal was defeated by a vote of 73-25
and the Senate is prepared to vote on a plan accepted by the
Clinton administration to tie payments to U.N. reforms.
</P>
<P>
"It makes no sense to deny our allies funds that we owe to them
and expect that they are going to be generous in negotiating
settlements with us in a whole host of agreements around the
globe," said Lugar.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration today accepted the basic elements of a
plan worked out with Chairman Jesse Helms of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee to pay 819 million U.S. dollars over three
years, with a demand of reducing U.S. dues and other U.N. reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, the administration said it strongly opposes some
provisions of the bill.
</P>
<P>
Senator Joseph Biden, a ranking democrat in the committee, said
that "ideally, we should not have to add such conditions" on
paying the overdue U.N. dues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
