<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cameroun's New Parliament Held First Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Cameroun's new National Assembly
opened its first ordinary session in Yaounde this afternoon,
which marked the start of a five year mandate of the
parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony took place in the presence of the
government led by Cameroun's Prime Minister Peter Mafany Musonge.
</P>
<P>
Out of seven political parties that are going into the
parliament, five of them were present: the ruling Cameroun
People's Democratic Movement (CPDM), the Social Democratic Front,
the National Union for Democracy and Progress, the Union for
Democracy and Change and the Liberty Movement for Camerounian
Youth while the Movement for Democracy and the Republic and the
Union for the People of Cameroun did not take up their seats.
</P>
<P>
During the session, the parliamentarians have their mandate
validated and a Bureau of House will be elected.
</P>
<P>
Today's session was chaired by the Provisional Bureau that was
designated to run the affairs of house comprising of the eldest
member of the parliament and two youngest members of the house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
