<DOCNO> XIE19970618.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Unveils U.S. Economic Plans for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 17 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Tuesday announced a package of proposals of what was described
as trade and investment incentives to promote economic
development for Africa.
</P>
<P>
"This is a moment of tremendous promise for the people of
Africa," Clinton said in unveiling the measures, which he said
were designed to "bring hope to hundreds of millions living on
the African continent."
</P>
<P>
According to the proposals, the poorest countries in Africa
will receive duty-free access for some 1,800 additional
products, while any nation "undertaking concerted reforms" for
their economies will benefit from reduced tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The White House said Clinton will also use this week's G-7
summit in Denver to seek a coordinated international effort --
including urging the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund to provide debt relief for poor countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
